\h 1 Samuel
\id 1SA
\c 1
\p
\v 1 And there was a man of Ramathaim, a Zuphite of the hill-country of Ephraim, and his name was Elkanah, the son of Jerahmeel, the son of Elihu, the son of Toah, the son of Zuph, an Ephraimite.
\v 2 And he had two wives; the name of one was Hannah, and the name of the other Peninnah, and Peninnah had children, and Hannah had no children.
\v 3 And this man went up from his city from days to days to worship and to sacrifice to the \nd Lord\nd* of hosts in Shiloh. And Eli and his two sons, Hophni and Phinehas, priests to the \nd Lord\nd*, were there.
\v 4 And when the day came that Elkanah sacrificed, he gave to Peninnah his wife, and to all her sons and her daughters, portions:
\v 5 and he gave Hannah one portion\f + \fr 1:5 \ft cf. Deuteronomy 21:15-17; Exodus 21:8,10.\f*, because she had no child. However, he loved Hannah, and the \nd Lord\nd* had shut up her womb.
\v 6 And her rival provoked her greatly, to trouble her, because the \nd Lord\nd* had shut up her womb.
\v 7 And so he did year by year. When she went up to the house of the \nd Lord\nd*, she provoked her thus; and she wept, and didn't eat.
\v 8 And Elkanah her husband said to her, "Hannah"; and she said to him, "Here I am, my lord"; and he said to her, "Why do you weep, and why don't you eat, and why is your heart grieved? Am I not better than ten sons to you?"
\p
\v 9 And Hannah rose up after they had eaten in Shiloh and after they had drunk and stood before the \nd Lord\nd*. And Eli the priest was sitting upon his seat by the door-post of the temple of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 10 And her soul was bitter, and she prayed to the \nd Lord\nd*, and wept greatly.
\v 11 And she made a vow, and said, "O \nd Lord\nd* of hosts, if you will indeed look on the affliction of your handmaid, and remember me, and not forget your handmaid, and will give to your handmaid a seed of men, then I will give him as a Nazirite before you till the day of his death, and he will not drink wine or strong drink, and no razor will come upon his head."
\p
\v 12 And it happened as she multiplied praying before the \nd Lord\nd*, that Eli observed her mouth.
\v 13 And Hannah was speaking in her heart; only her lips moved, and her voice was not heard, and Eli thought she was drunk.
\v 14 And Eli said to her, "How long will you be drunk? Put your wine away from you."
\v 15 And Hannah answered and said, "No, my lord, I am a woman hard of day: I have drunk neither wine nor strong drink, and I have poured out my soul before the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 16 Don't count your handmaid as a daughter of belial\f + \fr 1:16 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f*; because I have lingered till now because of the abundance of my complaint and my provocation."
\v 17 And Eli answered and said, "Go in peace; and may the God of Israel grant your request that you have asked from him."
\v 18 And she said, "Let your handmaid find favour in your eyes." And the woman went her way, and when she came to the room, she ate with her husband and drank, and her face was no longer fallen.
\p
\v 19 And they rose up early in the morning, and worshipped before the \nd Lord\nd*, and returned, and came to their house at Ramah. And Elkanah knew Hannah his wife; and the \nd Lord\nd* remembered her.
\v 20 And it happened when the time had come about, that Hannah conceived, and bore a son; and she called his name Samuel, "Because I have asked him of the \nd Lord\nd*."
\p
\v 21 And the man Elkanah, and all his house, went up to offer the sacrifice of the days in Shiloh, and to redeem all his vows and all the tithes of his hand.
\v 22 And Hannah didn't go up, because she said to her husband, "Until the child comes up when I have weaned him, that he may appear before the \nd Lord\nd*, and stay there forever."
\v 23 And Elkanah her husband said to her, "Do what is good in your eyes; wait until you have weaned him; only may the \nd Lord\nd* confirm what goes forth from your mouth." And the woman waited and nursed her son until she weaned him.
\v 24 And she went up when she had weaned him, with a three-year-old bull and bread and one ephah of meal, and a jug of wine. And she came to the house of the \nd Lord\nd* in Shiloh, and the child was with them.
\v 25 And they went before the \nd Lord\nd*, and his father slaughtered the offering, as he did from year to year to the \nd Lord\nd*; and she took the child, and he slaughtered the bull. And Hannah, the mother of the child, went to Eli.
\v 26 And she said, "O my lord, as your soul lives, I am the woman that stood here by you, praying to the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 27 I prayed for this child, and the \nd Lord\nd* has given me my request that I asked of him:
\v 28 so I have also given him to the \nd Lord\nd*. As long as he lives he is given to the \nd Lord\nd*." And he worshipped the \nd Lord\nd* there.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 And Hannah prayed, and said:
\q1 "My heart exults in the \nd Lord\nd*; my horn is exalted in my God;
\q1 my mouth is enlarged over my enemies.
\q1 I rejoice in your salvation for
\v 2 \q1 there is no-one holy as the \nd Lord\nd*,
\q1 for there is no-one righteous like our God, nor is there any rock
\q1 besides you.
\v 3 \q1 Don't boast, and don't speak proudly;
\q1 don't let arrogance come out of your\sup ‡\sup* mouth,
\q1 for the \nd Lord\nd* is a God of knowledge, and a God who weighs his
\q1 actions\f + \fr 2:3 \ft "Are not my actions weighed?", Ezekiel 18:29; 25; cf. Isaiah 40:13.\f*.
\v 4 \q1 The bows of the mighty men are broken,
\q1 and those who stumbled are girded with strength.
\v 5 \q1 Those who were full have hired out themselves for bread;
\q1 and those who were hungry have ceased.
\q1 Also, the barren has borne seven, and she who has many children
\q1 languishes.
\v 6 \q1 The \nd Lord\nd* kills and makes alive.
\q1 He brings down to Sheol, and brings up.
\v 7 \q1 The \nd Lord\nd* makes poor and makes rich.
\q1 He brings low, he also lifts up.
\v 8 \q1 He raises up the poor out of the dust; he lifts up the needy from
\q1 the rubbish heap,
\q1 to make them sit with princes, and inherit the throne of glory.
\q1 For the pillars of the earth are the \nd Lord\nd*'s, and he has set the world
\q1 upon them.
\v 9 \q1 He will keep the feet of his holy ones, and the wicked will be put
\q1 to silence in darkness.
\q1 He gives his petition to the one who prays, and he blesses the years
\q1 of the righteous,
\q1 for no man will prevail by strength.
\v 10 \q1 The \nd Lord\nd* shatters his adversaries. The \nd Lord\nd* is holy.
\q1 The \nd Lord\nd* has gone up in the heavens, and he has thundered.
\q1 He will judge the ends of the earth, and he will give strength to our
\q1 king, and exalt the horn of his anointed."
\p
\v 11 And she left him there before the \nd Lord\nd*, and went to Ramah. And the child ministered to the \nd Lord\nd* before Eli the priest.
\p
\v 12 And the sons of Eli were sons of belial\f + \fr 2:12 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f*; they didn't know the \nd Lord\nd*,
\v 13 and the custom of the priests with the people. When any man offered sacrifice, the priest's servant came while the flesh was boiling with a flesh-hook of three teeth in his hand,
\v 14 and he thrust it into the pan, or kettle, or cauldron, or pot. All that the flesh-hook brought up the priest took for himself. So they did in Shiloh to all the Israelites that came to sacrifice to the \nd Lord\nd*:
\v 15 even before they burnt the fat, the priest's servant came, and said to the man that sacrificed, "Give flesh to roast for the priest; because he will not have boiled flesh from the pan from you."
\v 16 And the man who was sacrificing said to him, "Let the fat be burnt first, and take as much as your soul desires," and he said, "No, for you must give it to me now, and if not, I will take it by force."
\v 17 And the sin of the young men was very great before the \nd Lord\nd*, for they despised the offering of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\p
\v 18 And Samuel ministered before the \nd Lord\nd*, being a child, girded with a linen ephod.
\v 19 And his mother made him a little robe, and brought it to him from days to days, when she came up with her husband to offer the sacrifice of the days.
\v 20 And Eli blessed Elkanah and his wife, and said, "May the \nd Lord\nd* repay you seed from this woman in place of the gift that you have given to the \nd Lord\nd*." And the man went to his own place.
\v 21 And the \nd Lord\nd* visited Hannah, and she conceived, and bore three sons and two daughters. And the child Samuel grew before the \nd Lord\nd*.
\p
\v 22 And Eli was very old; and he heard what his sons did to the sons of Israel, and how they lay with the women who did service at the door of the tent of meeting.
\v 23 And he said to them, "Why do you do such things that I hear being said of you from the mouth of the \nd Lord\nd*'s people?
\v 24 No, my sons, for the report that I hear isn't good. Don't do this, for the reports that I hear are not good, so that the people don't serve God.
\v 25 If one man sins against another, they may pray to the \nd Lord\nd* for him, and if a man sins against the \nd Lord\nd*, who will intercede for him?" However, they didn't listen to the voice of their father, because the \nd Lord\nd* was minded to put them to death.
\p
\v 26 And the child Samuel went on, and was good both with the \nd Lord\nd*, and with men.
\v 27 And a man of God came to Eli, and said, "Thus says the \nd Lord\nd*, 'I revealed myself to the house of your father, when they were in Egypt, slaves to Pharaoh's house,
\v 28 and I chose the house of your father out of all the tribes of Israel to serve me as priests, to go up to my altar, to burn incense, to wear an ephod before me, and I gave to the house of your father as food all the offerings of the children of Israel made by fire.
\v 29 Why do you look at my sacrifice and at my offering with distress of eye\f + \fr 2:29 \ft cf. first part 18:9; Genesis 42:21.\f* and honour your sons above me, to be blessed with the first of all the offerings of Israel before me?'
\v 30 Therefore the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, says, 'I said that your house, and the house of your father, should walk before me for ever;' and now the \nd Lord\nd* says, 'Far be it from me; for those who honour me I will honour, and those who despise me will be lightly esteemed.
\v 31 Behold, the days are coming when I will cut off your seed and the seed of your father's house,
\v 32 and you will not have an old man in my house forever.
\v 33 And one man of yours I will not cut off from my altar, to waste away his eyes and to pine away his soul; and all the increase of your house will fall by the swords of men.
\v 34 And this will be the sign to you that will come upon your two sons, on Hophni and Phinehas: in one day both of them will die.
\v 35 And I will raise up a faithful priest for myself who will do according to that which is in my heart and in my mind: and I will build him a faithful house; and he will walk before my anointed forever.
\v 36 And it will happen that every one who is left in your house will come and bow down to him for a piece of silver and a loaf of bread, and say, "Please put me into one of the priests' offices, so that I may eat a morsel of bread."'"
\c 3
\p
\v 1 And the child Samuel ministered to the \nd Lord\nd* before Eli. And the word of the \nd Lord\nd* was precious in those days; no vision spread abroad.
\p
\v 2 And it happened at that time, when Eli had laid down in his place (and his eyes had begun to grow dim; he couldn't see),
\v 3 and the lamp of God hadn't yet gone out, and Samuel had laid down in the temple of the \nd Lord\nd*, where the ark of God was,
\v 4 that the \nd Lord\nd* called and said, "Samuel, Samuel"; and he said, "Here I am."
\v 5 And he ran to Eli, and said, "Here I am, for you called me." And he said, "I didn't call; lie down again." And he went and lay down.
\v 6 And the \nd Lord\nd* called yet again, "Samuel, Samuel." And he rose and went to Eli, and said, "Here I am, for you called me." And he answered, "I didn't call, my son; lie down again."
\v 7 And Samuel didn't yet know God, neither had the word of the \nd Lord\nd* been revealed to him yet.
\v 8 And the \nd Lord\nd* called Samuel again the third time. And he rose and went to Eli, and said, "Here I am; for you called me." And Eli perceived that the \nd Lord\nd* had called the child,
\v 9 and Eli said to Samuel, "Go, lie down: and it will be, if he calls you, that you will say, 'Speak, \nd Lord\nd*; for your servant hears.'" And Samuel went and lay down in his place.
\p
\v 10 And the \nd Lord\nd* came, and stood and called as at other times, "Samuel, Samuel." And Samuel said, "Speak; for your servant hears."
\v 11 And the \nd Lord\nd* said to Samuel, "Behold, I will do a thing in Israel, at which both the ears of every one who hears it will tingle.
\v 12 In that day I will raise up against Eli all that I have spoken concerning his house, from the beginning even to the end.
\v 13 For I have told him that I will judge his house forever, for the iniquity of his sons, because his sons spoke evil against God, and he didn't dim them.
\v 14 And not so; I have promised to the house of Eli, that the iniquity of Eli's house will not be expiated with sacrifice nor offering forever."
\p
\v 15 And Samuel lay until the morning, and rose early in the morning, and opened the doors of the house of the \nd Lord\nd*. And Samuel feared to show Eli the vision.
\v 16 And Eli called Samuel, and said, "Samuel, my son." And he said, "Here I am."
\v 17 And he said, "What is the word which he has spoken to you? Please don't hide it from me: God do so to you, and more also, if you hide anything from me of all the things that he spoke to you in your ears."
\v 18 And Samuel told him every word, and hid nothing from him. And he said, "It is the \nd Lord\nd*: let him do what is good in his eyes."
\v 19 And Samuel grew, and the \nd Lord\nd* was with him, and let none of his words fall to the ground.
\v 20 And all Israel from Dan even to Beer-sheba knew that Samuel was faithful as a prophet of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 21 And the \nd Lord\nd* appeared again in Shiloh; for the \nd Lord\nd* revealed himself to Samuel. And Samuel was faithful as a prophet of the \nd Lord\nd* to all Israel from one end of the land to the other. And Eli was very old, and his sons kept going on, and their way was evil before the \nd Lord\nd*.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 And in those days the Philistines gathered against Israel to make war; and Israel went out to meet them in battle, and camped beside Eben-ezer: and the Philistines camped in Aphek.
\v 2 And the Philistines put themselves in array against Israel: and the battle turned, and Israel was struck before the Philistines; and they killed about four thousand men of the army in the field.
\p
\v 3 And when the people had come into the camp, the elders of Israel said, "Why has the \nd Lord\nd* struck us today before the Philistines? Let us bring the ark of our God to us from Shiloh, that it may come among us, and save us out of the hand of our enemies."
\v 4 And the people sent to Shiloh; and they brought the ark of the covenant of the \nd Lord\nd* of hosts, who sits \add above\add* the cherubim, from there: and the two sons of Eli, Hophni and Phinehas, were there with the ark of the covenant of God.
\v 5 And when the ark of the covenant of the \nd Lord\nd* came into the camp, all Israel shouted with a great shout, and the earth resounded.
\v 6 And when the Philistines heard the shout, they said, "What is this great shout in the camp of the Hebrews?" And they understood that the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* had come into the camp.
\v 7 And the Philistines were afraid, and they said, "These are the gods that have come to them into the camp." And they said, "Woe to us! For no such thing has happened previously\f + \fr 4:7 \ft Hebrew: yesterday and the third day.\f*.
\v 8 Woe to us! Who will deliver us out of the hand of these mighty gods? These are the gods that struck the Egyptians with all kinds of plagues, and in the wilderness.
\v 9 Be strong, and be men, O Philistines, that you may not be servants to the Hebrews, as they have been to you: be men, and fight them."
\v 10 And the Philistines fought them, and Israel was struck, and they fled every man to his tent: and there was a very great slaughter; for there fell 30,000 foot soldiers of Israel.
\v 11 And the ark of God was taken; and the two sons of Eli, Hophni and Phinehas, were killed.
\p
\v 12 And a man of Benjamin ran out of the army, and came to Shiloh the same day, with his clothes torn, and with earth on his head.
\v 13 And when he came, behold, Eli was sitting on the seat by the gate, watching the road; for his heart trembled for the ark of God. And when the man came into the city, and told it, all the city cried out.
\v 14 And when Eli heard the sound of the crying, he said, "What is the sound of this crying?" And the man hurried, and came and told Eli.
\v 15 And Eli was ninety eight years old; and his eyes were set, and he couldn't see. And Eli said to those who were standing around him, What is the sound of this tumult?
\v 16 And the man said to Eli, "I am the one who came out of the army, and I fled today out of the army." And he said, "How did it go, my son?"
\v 17 And the one who brought the news answered and said, "Israel has fled before the Philistines, and there has also been a great slaughter among the people, and your two sons also are dead, and the ark of God is taken."
\v 18 And it happened, when he made mention of the ark of God, that he fell backwards off his seat by the side of the gate; and his neck broke, and he died: for he was an old man, and heavy. And he had judged Israel twenty years.
\p
\v 19 And his daughter-in-law, Phinehas' wife, was with child, about to give birth: and when she heard the news that the ark of God was taken, and that her father-in-law and her husband were dead, she bowed herself and gave birth, for her pains came upon her.
\v 20 And when her time came, she was about to die, and the women that stood by her said to her, "Don't be afraid, for you have given birth to a son." And she neither answered nor paid attention.
\v 21 And she named the child Ichabod\f + \fr 4:21 \ft The name means "Woe to the glory".\f*, because of the ark of God, and because of her father-in-law and her husband.
\v 22 And she said, "The glory of Israel departed when the ark of God was taken."
\c 5
\p
\v 1 And the Philistines had taken the ark of God, and they brought it from Eben-ezer to Ashdod.
\v 2 And the Philistines took it and brought it into the house of Dagon, and set it by Dagon.
\v 3 And when the people of Ashdod rose early the next day, behold, Dagon had fallen on his face to the ground before the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*. And they raised Dagon up, and set him in his place again.
\v 4 And when they arose early on the next morning, behold, Dagon had fallen on his face to the ground before the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*; and the head of Dagon and both the soles of his feet were cut off on the threshold, and both the palms of his hands were fallen on the threshold; only the back of Dagon was left to him.
\v 5 Therefore neither the priests of Dagon nor anyone who comes into Dagon's house tread on the threshold of Dagon in Ashdod to this day, for they leap over it.
\p
\v 6 And the hand of the \nd Lord\nd* was heavy on the people of Ashdod, and he destroyed them, and struck them with swellings, Ashdod and its borders. And he brought mice on them, and they swarmed in their ships, and mice went up into their land; and there was a deadly confusion in the city.
\v 7 And when the men of Ashdod saw that it was so, they said, "The ark of God will not stay with us; for his hand is hard on us, and on Dagon our god."
\v 8 And they sent and gathered all the lords of the Philistines to them, and said, "What will we do with the ark of the God of Israel?" And they answered, "Let the ark of the God of Israel be carried around to us." And the ark of God was brought to Gath.
\v 9 And it happened that after it was brought to Gath, the hand of the \nd Lord\nd* was against the city with a very great turmoil: and he struck the men of the city, both small and great with swellings.
\v 10 And the men of Gath made golden swellings for themselves; and mice swarmed among them. And they sent the ark of God to Ekron. And it happened, as the ark of God came to Ekron, that the Ekronites cried out, saying, "Why have you brought the ark of the God of Israel around to us, to kill us and our people?"
\v 11 And they sent and gathered together all the lords of the Philistines, and they said, "Send away the ark of the God of Israel, and let it go to its own place again, that it may not kill us and our people." For there was a deadly turmoil throughout all the city, when the ark of God came there.
\v 12 And the men that lived, and didn't die, were struck with the swellings; and the cry of the city went up to heaven.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 And the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* was in the country of the Philistines seven months; and their land swarmed with mice.
\v 2 And the Philistines called for the priests and the diviners, saying, "What will we do with the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*? Show us with what to send it to its place."
\v 3 And they said, "If you send away the ark of the covenant of the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, don't send it empty, for by all means return him a guilt offering: then you will be healed, and atonement will be made for you. Why should his hand not be removed from you?"
\v 4 And they said, "What will be the guilt offering which we will return to him?" And they said, "Five golden swellings, the number of the lords of the Philistines; for one plague was on you, and on your lords, and on the people.
\v 5 And you will make images of your swellings, and images of your mice that destroy the land; and you will give glory to the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel: perhaps he will lighten his hand from you, and from your gods, and from your land.
\v 6 And why do you harden your hearts, as the Egyptians and Pharaoh hardened their hearts? When he had mocked among them, didn't they let the people go, and they departed?
\v 7 And now take and prepare a new cart, and two milk cows without their calves; and hitch the cows to the cart, and bring their calves home, away from them;
\v 8 and take the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*, and place it on the cart; and put the articles of gold, which you are returning to him for a guilt offering, in a box by its side; and send it away, and it will go.
\v 9 And watch; if it goes up by the way of its own border to Beth-shemesh, he has done us this great evil: and if not, then we will know that it isn't his hand that struck us; it was a chance that happened to us.
\p
\v 10 And the men did so, and took two milk cows and tied them to the cart, and shut up their calves at home;
\v 11 and they put the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* on the cart, and the mice of gold, and the swellings of gold; and they put the box by its side.
\v 12 And the cows took the straight way by the way to Beth-shemesh; they went along the highway, mooing as they went, and didn't turn aside to the right hand or to the left; and the lords of the Philistines went after them to the border of Beth-shemesh.
\p
\v 13 And \add the people of\add* Beth-shemesh were reaping their wheat harvest in the valley; and they lifted up their eyes, and saw the ark, and rejoiced to meet it.
\v 14 And the cart came into the field of Joshua the Beth-shemite, and stood there, beside a great stone: and they split the wood of the cart, and offered up the cows for a burnt offering to the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 15 And the Levites took down the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*, and the box that was with it, which had the articles of gold in it, and put them on the great stone: and the men of Beth-shemesh offered burnt offerings and sacrificed sacrifices the same day to the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 16 And when the five lords of the Philistines had seen it, they returned to Ekron the same day.
\v 17 And these are the golden swellings which the Philistines returned for a guilt offering to the \nd Lord\nd*: one for Ashdod, one for Gaza, one for Ashkelon, one for Gath, one for Ekron;
\v 18 and the golden mice, according to the number of all the cities of the Philistines belonging to the five lords, both of fortified cities and of country villages. And the great stone upon which they set down the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* is to this day in the field of Joshua the Beth-shemite.
\p
\v 19 And the sons of Jechoniah didn't rejoice with the men of Beth-shemesh, when they saw the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*; and he struck down 70 men of them. And the people mourned, because the \nd Lord\nd* had struck the people with a great slaughter.
\v 20 And the men of Beth-shemesh said, "Who is able to stand before the \nd Lord\nd*, this holy God? And who will the ark of the \nd Lord\nd* go up to from us?"
\v 21 And they sent messengers to the inhabitants of Kiriath-jearim, saying, "The Philistines have brought back the ark of the \nd Lord\nd*; come down, and take it up to you."
\c 7
\p
\v 1 And the men of Kiriath-jearim came, and fetched up the ark of the covenant of the \nd Lord\nd*, and brought it into the house of Abinadab in the hill, and sanctified Eleazar his son to keep the ark of the covenant of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 2 And it happened, from the day that the ark stayed in Kiriath-jearim that the time was long; for it was twenty years: and all the house of Israel turned after the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 3 And Samuel spoke to all the house of Israel, saying, "If you are returning to the \nd Lord\nd* with all your heart, put away the foreign gods and the Asherim\f + \fr 7:3 \ft Or, groves. The word in Hebrew is plural of Asherah, usually identified with a Canaanite fertility goddess.\f* from among you, and direct your hearts to the \nd Lord\nd*, and serve him only; and he will deliver you out of the hand of the Philistines."
\v 4 And the children of Israel did put away the Masters\f + \fr 7:4 \ft The Hebrew word is Baalim, plural of Baal. It is probably intended as a proper noun here referring to the chief Canaanite god, but the word is identical with the common noun 'master'.\f* and the Ashtaroth\f + \fr 7:4 \ft Ashtaroth is plural of Ashtoreth, the name of a Canaanite goddess supposedly associated with the moon and fertility.\f*, and served the \nd Lord\nd* only.
\v 5 And Samuel said, "Gather all Israel to Mizpah, and I will pray to the \nd Lord\nd* for you."
\v 6 And they gathered together to Mizpah, and drew water, and poured it out before the \nd Lord\nd*, and fasted on that day, and said there, "We have sinned against the \nd Lord\nd*." And Samuel judged the children of Israel in Mizpah.
\p
\v 7 And when the Philistines heard that the children of Israel were gathered together to Mizpah, the lords of the Philistines went up against Israel. And when the children of Israel heard it, they were afraid of the Philistines.
\v 8 And the children of Israel said to Samuel, "Don't stop crying to the \nd Lord\nd* our God for us, that he will save us out of the hand of the Philistines."
\v 9 And Samuel took a sucking lamb, and offered it for a whole burnt offering to the \nd Lord\nd*: and Samuel cried to the \nd Lord\nd* for Israel; and the \nd Lord\nd* answered him.
\v 10 And as Samuel was offering up the burnt offering, the Philistines drew near to battle against Israel; and the \nd Lord\nd* thundered on the Philistines with a great thunder on that day, and crushed them; and they were struck down before Israel.
\v 11 And the men of Israel went out of Mizpah, and pursued the Philistines, and struck them, until they came below Beth-car.
\p
\v 12 And Samuel took a stone, and set it between Mizpah and Jeshanah, and named it the Help Stone, saying, "The \nd Lord\nd* has helped us this far."
\v 13 And the \nd Lord\nd* subdued the Philistines, and they didn't come within the border of Israel any more: and the hand of the \nd Lord\nd* was against the Philistines all the days of Samuel.
\v 14 And the cities which the Philistines had taken from Israel were restored to Israel, from Ekron even to Gath; and they delivered their border out of the hand of the Philistines. And there was peace between Israel and the Amorites.
\v 15 And Samuel judged Israel all the days of his life.
\v 16 And he went from year to year in circuit to Beth-el, and Gilgal, and Mizpah; and he judged Israel in all those places.
\v 17 And his return was to Ramah, for his house was there; and there he judged Israel: and he built there an altar to the \nd Lord\nd*.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 And it happened, when Samuel was old, that he made his sons judges over Israel.
\v 2 And these were the names of his sons: the first-born was Joel; and the name of his second, Abijah: they were judges in Beer-sheba.
\v 3 And his sons didn't walk in his way, and turned aside after profit, and took bribes, and perverted justice.
\v 4 And the men of Israel gathered themselves together, and came to Samuel at Ramah;
\v 5 and they said to him, "Behold, you are old, and your sons don't walk in your way: and now make us a king to judge us like all the nations."
\v 6 And the thing was evil in the eyes of Samuel, when they said, "Give us a king to judge us." And Samuel prayed to the \nd Lord\nd*.
\p
\v 7 And the \nd Lord\nd* said to Samuel, "Listen to the voice of the people in all that they say to you; for they haven't rejected you, for they have rejected me, that I should not be king over them.
\v 8 According to all the works which they have done since the day that I brought them up out of Egypt even to this day, in that they have forsaken me, and served other gods, so they also do to you.
\v 9 And now listen to their voice: however you will testify to them, and you will show them the justice of the king that will reign over them.
\p
\v 10 And Samuel told all the words of the \nd Lord\nd* to the people that asked him for a king.
\v 11 And he said, "This will be the justice of the king who will reign over you: he will take your sons, and appoint them to himself, for his chariots, and to be his horsemen; and they will run before his chariots;
\v 12 and he will appoint them to himself for captains of thousands, and captains of hundreds, and to plough his ground, and to reap his harvest, and to gather his grapes, and to make his instruments of war, and the instruments of his chariots.
\v 13 And he will take your daughters to be perfumers, and to be cooks, and to be bakers.
\v 14 And he will take your fields, and your vineyards, and your olive groves, even the best of them, and give them to his servants.
\v 15 And he will take the tenth of your seed, and of your vineyards, and give to his officers, and to his servants.
\v 16 And he will take your men-servants, and your maid-servants, and your best cattle, and your donkeys, and tithe them for his work.
\v 17 And he will take the tenth of your flocks: and you will be his servants.
\v 18 And you will cry out in that day from before the face of your king you will have chosen for yourselves; and the \nd Lord\nd* will not answer you in those days, because you have chosen a king for yourselves.
\p
\v 19 And the people refused to listen to the voice of Samuel; and they said, "No, for we will have a king over us,
\v 20 that we also may be like all the nations, and that our king may judge us, and go out before us, and fight our battles."
\v 21 And Samuel heard all the words of the people, and he spoke them in the ears of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 22 And the \nd Lord\nd* said to Samuel, "Listen to their voice, and make a king to reign over them." And Samuel said to the men of Israel, "Every man go to his city."
\c 9
\p
\v 1 And there was a man of the children of Benjamin, whose name was Kish, the son of Abiel, the son of Zeror, the son of Bakir, the son of Aphiah, the son of a Benjamite, a mighty man of valour.
\v 2 And he had a son, whose name was Saul, a young and good man, and there wasn't a better person than he among the children of Israel: from his shoulders and upward he was taller than any of the people.
\p
\v 3 And some of the donkeys of Kish, Saul's father, were lost. And Kish said to Saul his son, "Take now one of the servants with you, and rise, go and look for the donkeys." And Saul rose, and took one of his father's servants with him, and went to look for the donkeys of Kish his father.
\v 4 And they passed through the hill-country of Ephraim, and passed through the land of Shalishah, and they didn't find them: and they passed through the land of Shaalim, and they weren't there: and they passed through the land of Jabin, and they didn't find them.
\p
\v 5 And they came to the land of Zuph, and Saul said to his servant who was with him, "Come, and let us return, lest my father stop caring for the donkeys, and be anxious for us."
\v 6 And he said to him, "Behold now, there is a man of God in this city, and he is a man that is held in honour; all that he says surely happens: now let us go there. Perhaps he can tell us about the journey we are on."
\v 7 And Saul said to his servant who was with him, "And, behold, if we go, what will we bring the man, for the bread in our vessels has run out, and there is no present to bring to the man of God: what do we have?"
\v 8 And the servant answered Saul again, and said, "Behold, I have in my hand a quarter of a shekel of silver: give that to the man of God, to tell us our way."
\v 9 (Before in Israel, when a man went to inquire of God, he said thus, "Come, and let us go to the seer;" for the people called a Prophet a Seer before.)
\v 10 And Saul said to his servant, "Your word is good; come, let us go." And they went to the city where the man of God was.
\p
\v 11 As they went up the ascent to the city, they found young maidens going out to draw water, and said to them, "Is the seer here?"
\v 12 And they answered them, and said, "He is; behold, \add he is\add* before you: now he has come, today, into the city; for the people have a sacrifice today in the high place.
\v 13 As soon as you have come into the city, you will find him straight away, before he goes up to the high place to eat; for the people will not eat until he comes, because he blesses the sacrifice; and afterwards those who are invited eat. And now go up; for you will find him at this time."
\v 14 And they went up to the city. As they came into the midst of the city, behold, Samuel came out toward them, to go up to the high place.
\p
\v 15 And the \nd Lord\nd* had uncovered the ear of Samuel a day before Saul came, saying,
\v 16 "Tomorrow about this time I will send you a man out of the land of Benjamin, and you will anoint him to be prince over my people Israel; and he will save my people out of the hand of the Philistines: for I have seen the affliction of my people, because their cry has come to me."
\v 17 And when Samuel saw Saul, the \nd Lord\nd* said to him, "Behold, the man I spoke of to you! This one will have authority over my people."
\v 18 And Saul approached Samuel in the midst of the city, and said, "Tell me, please, where the seer's house is."
\v 19 And Samuel answered Saul, and said, "I am he; go up before me to the high place, for you will eat with me today: and in the morning I will let you go, and will tell you all that is in your heart.
\v 20 And as for your donkeys that were lost three days ago, don't set your mind on them; for they have been found. And who are the treasures of Israel for? Aren't they for you, and for all your father's house?"
\v 21 And Saul answered and said, "Am I not a Benjamite, of the smallest of the tribes of Israel, and of the least family of all the tribe of Benjamin? And why do you speak to me \add a word\add* like this word?
\p
\v 22 And Samuel took Saul and his servant, and brought them into the guest-chamber, and made them sit in a place at the head of those who were invited, who were about seventy persons.
\v 23 And Samuel said to the cook, "Bring the portion which I gave you, of which I said to you, "Set it aside."
\v 24 And the cook took up the thigh, and that which was on it, and set it before Saul. And Samuel said, "Behold, that which has been reserved! Set it before you and eat; because it has been kept from the people for you, until the appointed time. Break it." And Saul ate with Samuel that day.
\p
\v 25 And when they had come down from the high place into the city, they spread a bed for Saul on the roof, and he slept.
\v 26 And it happened about daybreak, that Samuel called to Saul on the roof, saying, "Get up, so I may send you on your way." And Saul rose, and they both went out, he and Samuel.
\v 27 As they were going down at the end of the city, Samuel said to Saul, "Bid the servant pass on before us, and you stand still first, so I may make you hear the word of God."
\c 10
\p
\v 1 And Samuel took the vial of oil, and poured it on his head, and kissed him, and said, "Hasn't the \nd Lord\nd* anointed you to be prince over his people, over Israel? And you will rule among the people of the \nd Lord\nd*, and you will save them from the hand of their enemies.
\v 2 And this will be the sign to you that the \nd Lord\nd* has anointed you a ruler over his inheritance: when you have departed from me today you will find two men by Rachel's sepulchre, within the border of Benjamin, rushing in the ascent; and they will say to you, 'The donkeys which you went to look for have been found; and, behold, your father has left off the matter\f + \fr 10:2 \ft Hebrew: words.\f* of the donkeys, and is anxious for you, saying, "What will I do for my son?"'
\v 3 And you will go on from there and you will come to the oak of Tabor; and there three men going up to God at Beth-el will meet you, one carrying three kids, and another carrying three bags of bread, and another carrying a bottle of wine:
\v 4 and they will ask you of your peace, and give you two wave offerings of bread, which you will receive from their hand.
\v 5 After that you will come to the hill of God, where the garrison of the Philistines is. It will happen when you have come to the city there, that you will meet a band of prophets coming down from the high place with a psaltery, and a timbrel, and a pipe, and a harp, before them; and they will be prophesying:
\v 6 and the Spirit of the \nd Lord\nd* will come on you mightily, and you will prophesy with them, and you will be turned into another man.
\v 7 And when these signs have come to you, do what your hand finds for you to do, for God is with you.
\v 8 And you will go down before me to Gilgal; and, behold, I will come down to you, to offer burnt-offerings, and to sacrifice sacrifices of peace-offerings: you will wait for seven days until I come to you and show you what you will do."
\p
\v 9 And it was so, that, when he had turned his back to go from Samuel, God gave him another heart: and all those signs happened that day.
\v 10 And when they came from there to the hill, behold, a band of prophets met him; and the Spirit of God came mightily upon him, and he prophesied among them.
\v 11 And it happened that all who knew him previously\f + \fr 10:11 \ft Hebrew, from yesterday and the third day.\f* saw that, behold, he prophesied with the prophets, and the people said to one another, "What is this that has come to the son of Kish? Is Saul also among the prophets?"
\v 12 And one of them answered and said, "And who is his father?" Therefore it became a proverb, "Is Saul also among the prophets?
\p
\v 13 And when he had finished prophesying, he came to the hill.
\v 14 And his uncle said to him and to his servant, "Where did you go?" And he said, "To look for the donkeys; and when we saw that they weren't found, we came to Samuel."
\v 15 And Saul's uncle said, "Please tell me what Samuel said to you."
\v 16 And Saul said to his uncle, "He told us plainly that the donkeys were found." And he didn't tell him about the word of the kingdom which Samuel had spoken of.
\p
\v 17 And Samuel called the people together to the \nd Lord\nd* at Mizpah;
\v 18 and he said to the children of Israel, "Thus says the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, "I brought up Israel out of Egypt, and I saved you from the hand of the Egyptians, and from the hand of all the kingdoms that oppressed you:
\v 19 and today you have rejected your God, who himself saves you from all your evils and your distresses; and you have said, 'No, for you will set a king over us.' And now present yourselves before the \nd Lord\nd* by your tribes, and by your families."
\p
\v 20 And Samuel brought all the tribes of Israel near, and the tribe of Benjamin was taken.
\v 21 And he brought the tribe of Benjamin near by their families; and the family of the Matrites was taken; and he brought the family of Matri near, man by man, and Saul the son of Kish was taken: and when they looked for him, he couldn't be found.
\v 22 And he asked further of the \nd Lord\nd*, "Has the man come here?" And the \nd Lord\nd* answered, "Behold, he has hidden himself among the baggage."
\v 23 And he ran and brought him from there, and he stood among the people; and he was taller than any of the people from his shoulders up.
\v 24 And Samuel said to all the people, "Do you see him who the \nd Lord\nd* has chosen, that there is none like him among you all?" And all the people shouted, and said, "May the king live!"
\p
\v 25 And Samuel told the people the justice of the kingdom, and wrote it in a book, and placed it before the \nd Lord\nd*. And Samuel sent all the people away, and they went every man to his place.
\v 26 And Saul also went to his house to Gibeah; and the sons of valour whose hearts God had touched went with Saul.
\v 27 And certain sons of belial\f + \fr 10:27 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f* said, "How will this man save us?" And they despised him, and brought him no present.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 And Nahash, the king of the Ammonites, had been oppressing the sons of Gad and the sons of Reuben grievously, and he put out the right eye of each of them, and allowed Israel no deliverer; and no man of the sons of Israel who were across the Jordan remained, whose right eye Nahash, king of the Ammonites hadn't put out; and 7,000 men had escaped from the Ammonites and entered into Jabesh-gilead. And about a month later Nahash the Ammonite came up, and camped against Jabesh-gilead: and all the men of Jabesh said to Nahash, "Make a covenant with us, and we will serve you."
\v 2 And Nahash the Ammonite said to them, "I will make it with you on this condition: that all your right eyes be put out; and I will make it for a reproach on all Israel."
\v 3 And the elders of Jabesh said to him, "Give us seven days' respite, that we may send messengers to all the borders of Israel; and if there is no one to save us, then we will come out to you."
\p
\v 4 And the messengers came to Gibeah of Saul, and spoke these words in the ears of the people: and all the people lifted up their voice, and wept.
\v 5 And, behold, Saul came following the oxen out of the field; and Saul said, "What is the matter with the people, why do they weep?" And they told him the words of the men of Jabesh.
\v 6 And the Spirit of the \nd Lord\nd* came mightily on Saul when he heard those words, and his anger was kindled greatly because of them.
\v 7 And he took a yoke of oxen, and cut them in pieces, and sent them throughout all the borders of Israel by the hand of messengers, saying, "Whoever doesn't come forth after Saul and after Samuel, so will it be done to his oxen." And the dread of the \nd Lord\nd* fell on the people, and they came out as one man.
\v 8 And he numbered them in Bezek at the high place; and the children of Israel were 600,000, and the men of Judah 70,000.
\p
\v 9 And he said to the messengers that had come, "Thus you will say to the men of Jabesh, 'Tomorrow, by the time the sun is hot, you will have deliverance.'" And the messengers came and told the men of Jabesh; and they were glad.
\v 10 And the men of Jabesh said to Nahash the Ammonite, "Tomorrow we will come out to you, and you will do with us all that is good in your eyes."
\v 11 And it happened on the next day, that Saul put the people into three companies; and they came into the midst of the camp in the morning watch, and struck the Ammonites until the heat of the day: and it happened that those who remained were scattered, and no two of them were left together.
\p
\v 12 And the people said to Samuel, "Who is the one who said, 'Saul will not reign over us?' Bring the men, that we may put them to death."
\v 13 And Samuel said, "Not a man will be put to death this day; for today the \nd Lord\nd* has worked salvation in Israel."
\v 14 And Samuel said to the people, saying, "Come, and let us go to Gilgal, and renew the kingdom there."
\v 15 And all the people went to Gilgal; and there Samuel anointed Saul king before the \nd Lord\nd* in Gilgal; and there they offered sacrifices of peace-offerings before the \nd Lord\nd*; and Samuel and all the men of Israel rejoiced greatly.
\c 12
\p
\v 1 And Samuel said to all Israel, "Behold, I have listened to your voice in all that you said to me, and have made a king over you.
\v 2 And now, behold, the king walks before you; and I am old and grey headed; and, behold, my sons are with you: and I have walked before you from my youth to this day.
\v 3 Here I am: answer against me before the \nd Lord\nd*, and before his anointed: whose ox have I taken, or whose donkey have I taken, or who have I defrauded? Who have I oppressed, or of whose hand have I taken a ransom or a pair of shoes\f + \fr 12:3 \ft c.f. Amos 2:6; 8:6.\f*? Accuse me and I will restore it to you."
\v 4 And they said to Samuel, "You haven't defrauded us, nor oppressed us, nor afflicted us, neither have you taken anything from any man's hand."
\v 5 And he said to them, "The \nd Lord\nd* is witness against you, and his anointed is witness this day, that you haven't found anything in my hand." And they said, "He is witness."
\p
\v 6 And Samuel said to the people, "The \nd Lord\nd* is witness, who appointed Moses and Aaron, and who brought your fathers up out of the land of Egypt.
\v 7 And now stand still, that I may judge you before the \nd Lord\nd*, and I will recount for you all the righteous acts of the \nd Lord\nd*, which he did to you and to your fathers,
\v 8 as when Jacob and his sons had come into Egypt, and the Egyptians oppressed them, and your fathers cried to the \nd Lord\nd*, and the \nd Lord\nd* sent Moses and Aaron, and he brought forth your fathers out of Egypt, and made them to dwell in this place.
\v 9 And they forgot the \nd Lord\nd* their God; and he sold them into the hand of Sisera, captain of the host of Jabin king of Hazor, and into the hand of the Philistines, and into the hand of the king of Moab; and they fought against them.
\v 10 And they cried to the \nd Lord\nd*, and they said, 'We have sinned, because we have forsaken the \nd Lord\nd*, and have served the Masters\f + \fr 12:10 \ft The Hebrew word is Baalim, plural of Baal. It is probably intended as a proper noun here referring to the chief Canaanite god, but the word is identical with the common noun 'master'.\f* and the Ashtaroth\f + \fr 12:10 \ft Ashtaroth is plural of Ashtoreth, the name of a Canaanite goddess supposedly associated with the moon and fertility.\f*: and now deliver us out of the hand of our enemies, and we will serve you.'
\v 11 And the \nd Lord\nd* sent Jerubbaal, and Barak, and Jephthah, and Samson, and delivered you out of the hand of your enemies on every side; and you lived in safety.
\v 12 And when you saw that Nahash the king of the children of Ammon came against you, you said to me, 'No, for a king will reign over us.'
\v 13 And now behold the king who you have chosen, and who you have asked for: and, behold, the \nd Lord\nd* has set a king over you.
\v 14 If you will fear the \nd Lord\nd*, and serve him, and listen to his voice, and not rebel against the mouth of the \nd Lord\nd*, and both you and also the king who reigns over you be followers of the \nd Lord\nd* your God, then he will deliver you.
\v 15 And if you will not listen to the voice of the \nd Lord\nd*, and rebel against the mouth of the \nd Lord\nd*, then the hand of the \nd Lord\nd* will be against you and against your king to destroy you.
\v 16 Also now stand still and see this great thing, which the \nd Lord\nd* will do before your eyes.
\v 17 Isn't it wheat harvest today? I will call to the \nd Lord\nd*, that he may send thunder and rain; and you will know and see that your wickedness is great, which you have done in the eyes of the \nd Lord\nd*, in asking for a king.
\p
\v 18 And Samuel called to the \nd Lord\nd*, and the \nd Lord\nd* sent thunder and rain that day: and all the people greatly feared the \nd Lord\nd* and Samuel.
\v 19 And all the people said to Samuel, "Pray for your servants to the \nd Lord\nd* your God, that we may not die; for we have added evil to all our sins, to ask for a king."
\v 20 And Samuel said to the people, "Don't be afraid; you have indeed done all this evil, only don't turn aside from following the \nd Lord\nd*, and serve the \nd Lord\nd* with all your heart:
\v 21 and don't turn aside after vain things which cannot profit or deliver, for they are vain.
\v 22 For the \nd Lord\nd* will not forsake his people for his great name's sake, because it has pleased the \nd Lord\nd* to make you a people for himself.
\v 23 And as for me, far be it from me that I should sin against the \nd Lord\nd* in ceasing to pray for you: and I will serve the \nd Lord\nd* and I will instruct you in the good and the right way.
\v 24 Only fear the \nd Lord\nd*, and serve him in truth with all your heart; for you have seen what great things he has done for you.
\v 25 And if you still do evil, you will be consumed, both you and your king.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 Saul was thirty years old when he began to reign; and he reigned forty years over Israel.
\v 2 And Saul chose for himself 3,000 men of Israel; 2,000 of them were with Saul in Michmash and on the mount of Beth-el, and 1,000 were with Jonathan in Gibeah of Benjamin: and he sent each man of the rest of the people to his tent.
\v 3 And Jonathan struck the garrison of the Philistines that was in Gibeah: and the Philistines heard of it. And Saul blew the trumpet throughout all the land, saying, "The slaves have rebelled."
\v 4 And all Israel heard, saying "Saul has struck the garrison of the Philistines", and Israel was also had in abomination by the Philistines. And the people were gathered together to Gilgal after Saul.
\p
\v 5 And the Philistines assembled themselves together to fight with Israel, and they brought up against Israel 3,000 chariots, and 6,000 horsemen, and people as the sand which is on the sea shore in multitude: and they came up, and camped in Michmash, eastward of Beth-horon.
\v 6 And the men of Israel saw that they were oppressed and distressed, and the people hid themselves in caves, and in thickets, and in rocks, and in coverts, and in pits.
\v 7 And they crossed the fords of the Jordan to the land of Gad and Gilead; and as for Saul, he was still in Gilgal, and all the people followed him trembling.
\p
\v 8 And he waited seven days, according to the set time that Samuel had set: and Samuel didn't come to Gilgal; and the people were scattered from him.
\v 9 And Saul said, "Bring the burnt offering here, and the peace offerings, so that I may offer them." And he offered the burnt offering.
\v 10 And it happened that, as soon as he had finished offering the burnt offering, behold, Samuel came; and Saul went out to meet him, that he might bless him.
\v 11 And Samuel said, "What have you done?" And Saul said, "Because I saw that the people were scattered from me, and that you didn't come within the set days, and that the Philistines assembled themselves together at Michmash;
\v 12 and I said, "Now the Philistines will come down upon me to Gilgal, and I haven't entreated the favour of the \nd Lord\nd*:" and I forced myself, and offered the burnt offering."
\v 13 And Samuel said to Saul, "You have acted foolishly; you haven't kept my command which the \nd Lord\nd* your God commanded you: for now the \nd Lord\nd* would have established your kingdom upon Israel for ever.
\v 14 And now your kingdom will not continue: the \nd Lord\nd* has sought for himself a man after his own heart, and the \nd Lord\nd* has appointed him to be prince over his people, because you haven't kept that which the \nd Lord\nd* commanded you."
\p
\v 15 And Samuel rose, and went from Gilgal, and the rest of the people went up after Saul to meet the army, and they went from Gilgal to Gibeah of Benjamin. And Saul numbered the people who were present with him, about 600 men.
\v 16 And Saul and Jonathan his son and the people who were present with them stayed in Geba of Benjamin and they wept; and the Philistines camped in Michmash.
\v 17 And the destroyers came out of the camp of the Philistines in three companies: one company turned to the way that leads to Ophrah, to the land of Shual;
\v 18 and another company turned to the way to Beth-horon; and another company turned to the road of Geba that looks down on the valley of Zeboim.
\p
\v 19 And there was no smith found throughout all the land of Israel; for the Philistines said, "So the Hebrews don't make swords or spears for themselves."
\v 20 And all the Israelites went down to the land of the Philistines, each man to sharpen his ploughshare, his mattock, his axe, and his goad;
\v 21 and there was a charge of a pim for sharpening the ploughshares and the mattocks; and three shekels for the forks and the axes, and for setting the goads.
\v 22 And it happened in the days of the battle of Michmash, that there was neither sword nor spear found in the hand of any of the people who were with Saul and Jonathan (and they were found with Saul and with Jonathan his son).
\v 23 And the garrison of the Philistines went out to the pass of Michmash.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 And a day came when Jonathan the son of Saul said to the young man who bore his armour, "Come, and let us go over to the Philistines' garrison, that is on the other side." And he didn't tell his father.
\v 2 And Saul stayed in the furthest part of Gibeah under the pomegranate-tree which is in Migron: and the people who were with him were about 600 men;
\v 3 and Ahijah, the son of Ahitub, Ichabod's brother, the son of Phinehas, the son of Eli, the priest of the \nd Lord\nd* in Shiloh, wearing an ephod. And the people didn't know that Jonathan had gone.
\v 4 And between the passes by which Jonathan sought to go over to the Philistines' garrison there was a rocky crag on the one side, and a rocky crag on the other side: and the name of the one was Bozez, and the name of the other Seneh.
\v 5 One crag was on the north in front of Michmash, and the other on the south in front of Geba.
\p
\v 6 And Jonathan said to the young man who bore his armour, "Come, and let us go over to the garrison of these uncircumcised: it may be that the \nd Lord\nd* will work for us; for the \nd Lord\nd* isn't constrained to save by many or by few."
\v 7 And his armour bearer said to him, "Do all that your heart desires: here I am with you; my heart is as your heart".
\v 8 And Jonathan said, "Behold, we will pass over to the men, and we will show ourselves to them.
\v 9 If they say to us, 'Wait until we come to you;' then we will stand still in our place, and will not go up to them.
\v 10 And if they say, 'Come up to us;' then we will go up; for the \nd Lord\nd* has delivered them into our hand: and this will be the sign to us."
\v 11 And both of them showed themselves to the garrison of the Philistines: and the Philistines said, "Behold, the Hebrews come forth out of the holes where they had hidden themselves."
\v 12 And the men of the garrison answered Jonathan and his armour bearer, and said, "Come up to us, and we will show you something." And Jonathan said to his armour bearer, "Come up after me; for the \nd Lord\nd* has delivered them into the hand of Israel."
\p
\v 13 And Jonathan climbed up on his hands and on his feet, and his armour bearer after him: and they turned towards Jonathan, and he struck them down, and his armour bearer put them to death after him.
\v 14 And that first slaughter, which Jonathan and his armour bearer made, was about twenty men, with arrows and slingstones and flints of the field.
\v 15 And there was a trembling in the camp, in the field, and among all the people; and the garrison and the destroyers trembled; and they would not labour; and the earth quaked: so there was a trembling from God.
\p
\v 16 And some of the watchmen of Saul in Gibeah of Benjamin looked; and, behold, the multitude was melting away, here and there.
\v 17 And Saul said to the people who were with him, "Number now, and see who has gone from us." And they numbered, and behold, Jonathan and his armour bearer weren't found.
\v 18 And Saul said to Ahijah, "Bring the ephod here;" for he wore the ephod at that time before Israel.
\v 19 And it happened, while Saul was talking to the priest, that the disturbance that was in the camp of the Philistines continued and increased: and Saul said to the priest, "Withdraw your hand."
\v 20 And Saul and all the people who were with him were gathered together, and came to the battle: and, behold, every man's sword was against his fellow, a very great confusion.
\v 21 And the slaves that were with the Philistines as previously\f + \fr 14:21 \ft Hebrew: yesterday and the third day.\f*, and that went up with them into the camp, even they also turned to be with the Israelites who were with Saul and Jonathan.
\v 22 And all the men of Israel who had hidden themselves in the hill country of Ephraim heard that the Philistines were fleeing and they also followed hard after them in the battle.
\v 23 And the \nd Lord\nd* saved Israel that day: and the battle passed over by Beth-horon. And all Israel was with Saul, about 10,000 men, and the battle spread into every city in the hill country of Ephraim.
\p
\v 24 And Saul committed a great error on that day, for he had bound the people with an oath, saying, "Any man who eats food until it is evening and I am avenged on my enemies is cursed." And none of the people\f + \fr 14:24 \ft That is, the army, as in Numbers 20:20, etc.\f* tasted food,
\v 25 and all the land tasted food. And a honeycomb was on the ground,
\v 26 and the people came to it; and the bees had gone, and no man put his hand to his mouth; for the people feared the promise.
\v 27 And Jonathan hadn't heard when his father made the people promise: and he reached out the end of the rod that was in his hand, and dipped it in the honeycomb, and put his hand to his mouth; and his eyes brightened.
\v 28 And one of the people answered and said, "Your father made the people promise a promise, saying, 'Whoever eats food this day is cursed.'" And the people were faint.
\v 29 And Jonathan knew, and he said, "My father has troubled the land: please see how my eyes have brightened because I tasted a little of this honey.
\v 30 How much more, if only the people had eaten freely today from the spoil of their enemies which they found! For now the slaughter among the Philistines would have been greater."
\p
\v 31 And they struck those of the Philistines that day at Michmash, and the people were very faint;
\v 32 and the people rushed upon the spoil, and took sheep, and cattle, and calves, and killed them on the ground; and the people ate them with the blood.
\v 33 And they told Saul, saying, "Behold, the people sin against the \nd Lord\nd*, in that they eat with the blood." And he said, "You\sup ‡\sup* have acted treacherously: roll a great stone here to me."
\v 34 And Saul said, "Disperse yourselves among the people, and say to them, 'Every man bring his ox, and every man bring his sheep here, and kill them here, and eat; and don't sin against the \nd Lord\nd* by eating with the blood.'" And all the people brought what every man had in his hand and slaughtered it there at night.
\v 35 And Saul built an altar to the \nd Lord\nd*: this was the first altar that he built to the \nd Lord\nd*.
\p
\v 36 And Saul said, "Let us go down after the Philistines by night, and take spoil among them until the morning light, and let us not leave a man of them." And they said, "Do whatever is good in your eyes." And the priest said, "Let us come near to God here."
\v 37 And Saul asked counsel from God, "Will I go down after the Philistines? Will you deliver them into the hand of Israel?" And he didn't answer him that day.
\v 38 And Saul said, "Come here, all you families of the people; and know and see who this sin has been in this day.
\v 39 For, as the \nd Lord\nd* lives, who saves Israel, though it be in Jonathan my son, he will surely die." And there wasn't a man among all the people who answered him.
\v 40 And he said to all the men of Israel, "You be on one side, and I and Jonathan my son will be on the other side." And the people said to Saul, "Do what is good in your eyes."
\v 41 And Saul said, "O \nd Lord\nd* God of Israel, why haven't you answered your servant today? If this guilt is on account of me or on account of Jonathan my son, O \nd Lord\nd* God of Israel, give Urim\f + \fr 14:41 \ft (lights)\f*; and if it is on account of your people Israel, give Thummim\f + \fr 14:41 \ft (perfections)\f*." And Jonathan and Saul were taken; and the people escaped.
\v 42 And Saul said, "Cast between me and Jonathan my son. Whoever the \nd Lord\nd* takes, let him die." And the people said to him, "Let it not be so;" and Saul prevailed over them, and they cast between him and Jonathan his son. And Jonathan was taken.
\p
\v 43 And Saul said to Jonathan, "Tell me what you have done." And Jonathan told him, and said, "I certainly did taste a little honey with the end of the rod that was in my hand; and, behold, I must die."
\v 44 And Saul said, "God do so to me and more also; for you will surely die today."
\v 45 And the people said to Saul, "Will the person who has worked this great salvation in Israel die today? Far from it: as the \nd Lord\nd* lives, not one hair of his head will fall to the ground; for he has worked with God this day." And the people interceded for Jonathan, and he didn't die.
\p
\v 46 And Saul went up from following the Philistines; and the Philistines went to their own place.
\v 47 And Saul took the kingdom, and he took property outside Israel, and he fought against all his enemies on every side, against Moab, and the children of Ammon, and against Edom, and Beth-rehob and the king of Zobah, and against the Philistines: and wherever he turned himself, he worked salvation.
\v 48 And he acted valiantly, and struck the Amalekites, and delivered Israel out of the hands of those who despoiled them.
\p
\v 49 And the sons of Saul were Jonathan, and Ishiah, and Malchishua, and Eshbaal; and the names of his two daughters were these: the name of the first-born Merob, and the name of the younger Michal:
\v 50 and the name of Saul's wife was Ahinoam the daughter of Ahimaaz. And the name of the captain of his host was Abiner the son of Ner, Saul's uncle.
\v 51 And Kish the father of Saul, and Ner the father of Abiner, were the sons of Abiel of Benjamin.
\v 52 And there was severe war against the Philistines all the days of Saul: and when Saul saw any mighty man, or any son of valour, he took him to himself.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 And Samuel said to Saul, "The \nd Lord\nd* sent me to anoint you to be king over his people, over Israel: and now listen to the voice of the words of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 2 Thus says the \nd Lord\nd* of hosts, 'I have noticed what Amalek did to Israel, how he met him in the way, when he came up out of Egypt.
\v 3 And now, go and strike Amalek, and completely destroy all that they have, and don't spare them; and kill both man and woman, infant and suckling, ox and sheep, camel and donkey.'"
\p
\v 4 And Saul summoned the people, and numbered them in Gilgal, 400,000 footmen, and 30,000 men of Judah.
\v 5 And Saul came to the cities of Amalek, and laid wait in the valley.
\v 6 And Saul said to the Kenites, "Go, depart from among Amalek, lest I destroy you with them; for you showed kindness to all the children of Israel, when they came up out of Egypt." And the Kenites departed from being among the Amalekites.
\v 7 And Saul struck the Amalekites, from Havilah as you go to Shur, that is before Egypt.
\v 8 And he took Agag the king of the Amalekites alive, and completely destroyed all the people with the edge of the sword.
\v 9 And Saul and the people spared Agag, and the best of the sheep, and of the oxen, and of the fatlings, and the lambs, and all that was good, and would not completely destroy them: and everything that was despised and worthless, that they completely destroyed.
\p
\v 10 And the word of the \nd Lord\nd* came to Samuel, saying,
\v 11 I repent that I have made Saul king; for he has turned back from following me, and hasn't raised up my words. And Samuel was angry; and he cried to the \nd Lord\nd* all night.
\v 12 And Samuel rose early and went to meet Israel in the morning; and it was told Samuel, saying, "Saul came to Carmel, and, behold, he set up a monument, and turned his chariot, and passed on, and went down to Gilgal."
\v 13 And Samuel came to Saul; and behold, he was offering a burnt offering to the \nd Lord\nd*, the first of the spoils that he had taken from Amalek; and Samuel came to Saul, and Saul said to him, "Blessed are you of the \nd Lord\nd*: I have raised up the word of the \nd Lord\nd*."
\v 14 And Samuel said, "And what is this sound of the sheep in my ears, and the sound of the cattle which I hear?"
\v 15 And Saul said, "I have brought them from Amalek: for the people spared the best of the sheep and of the cattle to sacrifice to the \nd Lord\nd* your God; and the rest I have completely destroyed."
\p
\v 16 And Samuel said to Saul, "Stay, and I will tell you what the \nd Lord\nd* has said to me this night." And he said to him, "Say on."
\v 17 And Samuel said, "Though you were little in your own eyes, weren't you made the head, being of the tribe of Benjamin, the smallest of the families of Israel? And the \nd Lord\nd* anointed you king over Israel;
\v 18 and the \nd Lord\nd* sent you on a journey, and said, 'Go, and completely destroy the sinners against me, the Amalekites, and fight against them until you have exterminated them.'
\v 19 And why didn't you obey the voice of the \nd Lord\nd*? And you flew upon the spoil, and did that which was evil in the eyes of the \nd Lord\nd*."
\p
\v 20 And Saul said to Samuel, "Yes, I have obeyed the voice of the people, and I have gone the way which the \nd Lord\nd* sent me, and have brought Agag the king of Amalek, and have completely destroyed the Amalekites.
\v 21 And the people took from the spoil, sheep and cattle, the chief of the devoted things, before the \nd Lord\nd* your God in Gilgal."
\v 22 And Samuel said, "Does the \nd Lord\nd* have as great delight in burnt offerings and sacrifices, as in obeying the voice of the \nd Lord\nd*? Behold, to obey is better than sacrifice, and to listen than the fat of rams.
\v 23 For rebellion is as the sin of witchcraft, and stubbornness is as the iniquity of teraphim\f + \fr 15:23 \ft 'Teraphim' is some kind of household idol, although the exact nature is unknown. See Genesis 31:19, 30, 34.\f*. Because you have rejected the word of the \nd Lord\nd*, he has also rejected you from being king over Israel."
\p
\v 24 And Saul said to Samuel, "I have sinned; for I have transgressed the commandment of the \nd Lord\nd*, and your words, because I feared the people, and obeyed their voice.
\v 25 And now, please, pardon my sin, and turn again with me, that I may worship the \nd Lord\nd*."
\v 26 And Samuel said to Saul, "I will not return with you; for you have rejected the word of the \nd Lord\nd*, and the \nd Lord\nd* has rejected you from being king over Israel."
\v 27 And as Samuel turned about to go away, he laid hold of the skirt of his robe, and it tore.
\v 28 And Samuel said to him, "The \nd Lord\nd* has torn the kingdom of Israel from you this day, and has given it to your neighbour, who is better than you.
\v 29 And Israel will be divided in two. And the Holy One of Israel will not turn nor repent; for he isn't like a man, that he should repent."
\p
\v 30 And Saul said, "I have sinned: yet honour me now, please, before the elders of my people, and before Israel, and turn again with me, that I may worship the \nd Lord\nd* your God."
\v 31 And Samuel turned again after Saul; and Saul worshipped the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 32 And Samuel said, "Bring Agag the king of the Amalekites here to me." And Agag came to him in bonds. And Agag said, "Would the bitterness of death have been thus?"
\v 33 And Samuel said to Agag, "As your sword has made women childless, so will your mother be childless among women." And Samuel cut Agag in pieces before the \nd Lord\nd* in Gilgal.
\v 34 And Samuel went to Ramah; and Saul went up to his house, to Gibeah.
\v 35 And Samuel didn't come to see Saul any more until the day of his death; for Samuel mourned for Saul: and the \nd Lord\nd* repented that he had made Saul king over Israel.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 And the \nd Lord\nd* said to Samuel, "How long will you mourn over Saul, for I have rejected him from being king over Israel? Fill your horn with oil and go; I will send you to Jesse, to Bethlehem, for I have seen a king for myself among his sons."
\v 2 And Samuel said, "How can I go? When Saul hears, he will kill me!" And the \nd Lord\nd* said, "Take a heifer with you and say, 'I have come to sacrifice to the \nd Lord\nd*.'
\v 3 And call Jesse to the sacrifice, and I will make you know what you will do. And you will anoint for me the one I say to you."
\v 4 And Samuel did all that the \nd Lord\nd* said to him, and came to Bethlehem. And the elders of the city came trembling to meet him, and they said, "Do you come in peace, O seer?"
\v 5 And he said, "Peace! I have come to sacrifice to the \nd Lord\nd*. Sanctify yourselves and rejoice with me today." And he sanctified Jesse and his sons and called them to the sacrifice.
\p
\v 6 And it happened when they entered that he saw Eliab and said, "Surely the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed is before him."
\v 7 And the \nd Lord\nd* said to Samuel, "Don't look at his appearance or at the greatness of his height, for I have rejected him, for God sees not as man sees, for man sees to the face, and the \nd Lord\nd* sees to the heart."
\v 8 And Jesse called to Amminadab and he passed before Samuel, and he said, "Neither has the \nd Lord\nd* chosen this one."
\v 9 And Jesse made Shammah pass \add before him\add*, and he said, "Neither has the \nd Lord\nd* chosen this one."
\v 10 And Jesse made seven of his sons pass before Samuel, and Samuel said to Jesse, "The \nd Lord\nd* hasn't chosen from among these."
\v 11 And Samuel said to Jesse, "Are these all the young men?" And he said, "The youngest still remains, and behold, he is tending the flock." And Samuel said to Jesse, "Send and bring him, for we will not go around until he comes here."
\v 12 And he sent and brought him, and he was reddish, with beautiful eyes and a good appearance to the \nd Lord\nd*, and the \nd Lord\nd* said, "Arise, anoint him, for this is he."
\v 13 And Samuel took the horn of oil and anointed him among his brothers. And the Spirit of the \nd Lord\nd* came mightily upon David from that day onward. And Samuel rose up and went to Ramah.
\p
\v 14 And the spirit of the \nd Lord\nd* left from \add being\add* with Saul and an evil spirit from the \nd Lord\nd* frightened him.
\v 15 And Saul's servants said to him, "Behold now, an evil spirit from the \nd Lord\nd* frightens you.
\v 16 Let our lord now command\f + \fr 16:16 \ft Hebrew, say to.\f* your servants before you, let them seek a man who knows how to play the harp, and it will be that when the evil spirit of God is on you, then he will play \add it\add* with his hand, and you will be well, it will let you alone."
\v 17 And Saul said to his servants, "Look for me now for a man who plays well, and bring him to me."
\v 18 And one of the young men answered and said, "Behold, I have seen a son of Jesse the Bethlehemite who knows how to play, a mighty, valiant man, and a man of battle, and understanding in speech, and a handsome man\f + \fr 16:18 \ft Hebrew, a man of form.\f*, and the \nd Lord\nd* is with him.
\p
\v 19 And Saul sent messengers to Jesse and said, "Send to me your son David who is with the flock."
\v 20 And Jesse took a donkey loaded with an omer of bread and a jug of wine, and one young goat, and sent them to Saul by his son David.
\v 21 And David came to Saul and stood before him, and he loved him greatly, and David became his armour bearer.
\v 22 And Saul sent to Jesse, saying, "Let David stand before me now, for he has found favour in my eyes."
\v 23 And it happened that when the evil spirit of God came to Saul, then David would take the harp and play \add it\add* with his hand and Saul would have relief, and be well, and the evil spirit would depart from upon him.
\c 17
\p
\v 1 And the Philistines gathered their armies for battle and they gathered at Socoh (which is Judah's), and they camped between Socoh and Azekah in Ephes-dammim.
\v 2 And Saul and the men of Israel gathered and camped in the valley of Elah and they arrayed for battle to meet the Philistines.
\v 3 And the Philistines stood on the mountain on this \add side\add* and Israel stood on the mountain on that \add side\add*, and the valley was between them.
\v 4 And a man between the two went out from the armies of the Philistines, named Goliath of Gath. His height was four cubits and a span\f + \fr 17:4 \ft A cubit is about the length of a man's thigh (Judges 3:16) so man's height is about four cubits. See also the account of the Generations and Kings (called 1 Chronicles 11:23) "a man of stature, five cubits high".\f*,
\v 5 and a helmet of bronze was on his head, and he was clothed with scaled armour, and the weight of the armour was five thousand shekels\f + \fr 17:5 \ft Archelological evidence suggests a weight between 9 and 17 grams for a shekel. Based on this Goliath's armour weighed between 45kg and 85kg, and his spear head weighed between 5½kg and 10kg.\f* of bronze and iron.
\v 6 And he had greaves of bronze upon his legs, and a javelin of bronze between his shoulders.
\v 7 And the shaft of his spear was like a weaver's beam, and the head of his spear was six hundred shekels of iron, and his shield bearer went before him.
\v 8 And he stood and called to the armies of Israel, and he said to them, "Why have you come out to array for battle against us? Am I not a Philistine, and you Saul's Hebrews? Choose a man for yourselves, and let him come down to me.
\v 9 If he is able to fight with me, and strike me, then we will be your servants, and if I prevail against him, and strike him, then you will be our servants, and serve us."
\v 10 And the Philistine said, "I defy the armies of Israel this day. Give me a man and let us fight together."
\v 11 And Saul and all Israel heard these words of the Philistine, and they were dismayed, and greatly afraid.
\p
\v 12 And David was the son of that Ephrathite of Bethlehem of Judah whose name was Jesse (and he had eight sons). And in the days of Saul the man came to be old, going on in years.
\v 13 And the three eldest\f + \fr 17:13 \ft Hebrew, great.\f* sons of Jesse had gone after Saul to the battle. And the names of his three sons who went to the battle were Eliab, the first-born, and his second, Abinadab, and the third Shammah.
\v 14 And David was the youngest, and the three eldest had gone after Saul.
\v 15 And David went and returned from Saul to feed his father's flock at Bethlehem.
\v 16 And the Philistine drew near morning and evening, and presented himself for forty days before Israel.
\v 17 And Jesse said to David his son, "Take now to your brothers an ephah of this roasted grain, and these ten loaves, and run to the camp, and give them to your brothers.
\v 18 And bring these ten cuttings of cheese to the captain of the thousand, and you will visit your brothers for peace, and bring their pledge.
\v 19 And Saul and they and every man of Israel were in the valley of Elah fighting with the Philistines.
\p
\v 20 And David got up early in the morning and left the flock with a keeper, and took \add the food\add* and went, as Jesse had commanded him. And he came to the track and the army was going out to the battle array and they shouted for the battle.
\v 21 And Israel and the Philistines put the battle in array, rank to meet rank.
\v 22 And David left his baggage in the hand of the keeper of the baggage and ran to the rank and came and asked his brothers as to \add their\add* peace.
\v 23 And he was speaking with them, and behold, the man between the two came up out of the ranks of the Philistines, Goliath the Philistine was his name, of Gath. And he spoke according to these words, and David heard them.
\v 24 And every man of Israel, when they saw the man, ran away from before him and were very much afraid.
\p
\v 25 And a man of Israel said, "Have you seen this man who has come up? He has surely come up to reproach Israel, and whoever strikes him, the king will enrich him with great riches, and he will give him his daughter, and make his father's house free in Israel."
\v 26 And David spoke to the men who stood by him, saying, "What will be done to the man who strikes this Philistine and takes away the reproach from Israel? For who is this uncircumcised Philistine, that he should reproach the armies of the living God?"
\v 27 And the people answered him according to this word\f + \fr 17:27 \ft That is, as in verse 25.\f*, saying, "So will it be done to the man who strikes him."
\v 28 And Eliab, his eldest brother, heard when he spoke to the men, and Eliab's anger burned against David, and he said, "Why have you come down, and who have you left that small flock with in the wilderness? I know your pride, and the evil of your heart, for you have come down to see the battle."
\v 29 And David said, "What have I done now? Wasn't it \add just\add* a word?"
\v 30 And he turned away from him to another and said the same thing, and the people answered him as before.
\v 31 And the words David spoke were heard, and they told them before Saul, and he received him.
\v 32 And David said to Saul, "Let no man's heart fail because of him! Your servant will go and fight with this Philistine."
\v 33 And Saul said to David, "You are not able to go and fight with this Philistine, for you are a young man, and he has been a man of war from his youth."
\v 34 And David said to Saul, "Your servant was tending among the flock for his father, and the lion came, and the bear, and took away a sheep from the flock,
\v 35 and I went out after him, and struck him, and I rescued it from his mouth, and when he rose against me I took hold of his beard and struck him and killed him.
\v 36 Your servant struck both the lion and the bear. This uncircumcised Philistine will be as one of them. Will I not go and strike him, and remove the reproach from Israel today? For who is that uncircumcised one, that he should taunt the armies of the living God?"
\v 37 And David said, "The \nd Lord\nd* who rescued me from the hand of the lion and from the hand of the bear, \add it is\add* he who will rescue me from the hand of this uncircumcised Philistine." And Saul said to David, "Go, and the \nd Lord\nd* be with you."
\p
\v 38 And Saul clothed David with his gear, and he put a helmet of brass on his head, and he clothed him with armour.
\v 39 And David put on his sword over his gear, and he wearied himself to walk, for he hadn't proved it. And David said to Saul, "I cannot walk with these, for I haven't proved them." And David took them off,
\v 40 and he took his staff in his hand, and he chose five smooth stones from the brook, and put them in the shepherds' bag which he had, that is, in a pouch, and his sling was in his hand, and he drew near to the Philistine.
\p
\v 41 And the Philistine came and drew near to David, and his shield bearer was before him.
\v 42 And the Philistine looked and saw David, and he disdained him, for he was a young man, and reddish, and with a beautiful appearance.
\v 43 And the Philistine said, "Am I a dog, that you come to me with sticks?" And the Philistine cursed David by his gods.
\v 44 And the Philistine said to David, "Come to me and I will give your flesh to the birds of the heavens and to the beasts of the field."
\v 45 And David said to the Philistine, "You come to me with a sword and with a spear and with a javelin, and I come to you in the name of the \nd Lord\nd* of hosts, the God of the armies of Israel who you have reproached.
\v 46 This day the \nd Lord\nd* will shut you up into my hand, and I will strike you and take off your head from you, and I will give your dead body and the dead bodies of the army of the Philistines to the birds of the heavens and to the wild beasts of the earth, and all the earth will know that there is a God for Israel,
\v 47 and all this assembly will know that the \nd Lord\nd* doesn't save with sword and spear, for the battle is the \nd Lord\nd*'s, and he will give you into our hand.
\p
\v 48 And it happened that when the Philistine rose and came and drew near to meet David, that David hurried and ran toward the rank to meet the Philistine.
\v 49 And David put his hand into his bag, and took a stone out of it, and he slung it and struck the Philistine in his forehead, and the stone sank through the helmet into his forehead, and he fell on his face to the earth.
\v 50 Thus David took hold of a sling and a stone on that day and struck the Philistine and killed him. And there was no sword in David's hand;
\v 51 and David ran and stood over the Philistine and took his sword and drew it out of its sheath and killed him, and cut off his head with it. And the Philistines saw that their warrior was dead, and they fled.
\v 52 And the men of Israel and Judah arose and shouted, and they pursued the Philistines until you come to Gath and to the gates of Ekron. And the wounded of the Philistines fell down by the way of Shaaraim, even to Gath and to Ekron.
\v 53 And the children of Israel returned from chasing after the Philistines and they plundered their camp.
\v 54 And David took the head of the Philistine and brought it to Jerusalem, and he put his armour in his tent.
\p
\v 55 And as Saul saw David go out against the Philistine, he said to Abiner, the captain of the host, "Whose son is this young man?" And Abiner said, "As your soul lives, O king, I don't know."
\v 56 And the king said, "Ask whose son this stripling is."
\v 57 And as David returned from striking the Philistine, Abiner took him, and brought him before Saul with the head of the Philistine in his hand.
\v 58 And Saul said to him, "Whose son are you, young man?" And David said, "The son of your servant Jesse, the Bethlehemite.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 And it happened that when he had finished speaking to Saul, that Jonathan saw David, and the soul of Jonathan was knit together with the soul of David, and Jonathan loved him as his own soul.
\v 2 And Saul took him that day, and would not let him return to his father's house.
\v 3 And Jonathan and David made a covenant, because he loved him as his own soul.
\v 4 And Jonathan took off the robe that he had on and gave it to David, and his gear, even to his sword and his bow and his belt. And Saul let him be over the men of war.
\v 5 And he went out and came in, and in whatever Saul sent him to do, he prospered. And it was good in the eyes of all the people, and also in the eyes of Saul's servants.
\p
\v 6 And it happened that as they came, as David returned from striking the Philistine, that the women came out of all the cities of Israel, singing and dancing, to meet king Saul with timbrels, with joy, and with musical instruments\f + \fr 18:6 \ft The Hebrew word suggests some kind of three-element musical instrument, such as a triangle or a three-stringed instrument.\f*.
\v 7 And the women who danced answered and said, "Saul has struck his thousands, and David his ten thousands."
\v 8 And Saul was very angry, and this word was evil in his eyes, and he said, "They have given David ten thousands, and me thousands. What more can he have? Only the kingdom!"
\v 9 And Saul was eyeing David from that day on.
\p
\v 10 And it happened on the next day that an evil spirit of God came mightily upon Saul and he prophesied in the midst of the house. And David was playing \add the harp\add* with his hand, as he did day by day. And Saul had his spear in his hand,
\v 11 and Saul raised the spear, and he said, "I will strike David, and the wall." And twice David turned aside from before him.
\v 12 And Saul was afraid of David, because the \nd Lord\nd* was with him and had departed from Saul.
\v 13 And Saul removed him from \add being\add* before him, and made him his captain over a thousand, and he went out and came before the people.
\v 14 And David behaved wisely in all his ways, and the \nd Lord\nd* was with him.
\v 15 And Saul saw that he behaved himself very wisely, and he feared him.
\v 16 And all Israel and Judah loved David, for he went out and came before the people.
\p
\v 17 And Saul said to David, "Behold my elder daughter Merob; I will give her to you for a wife; only be a son of valour for me, and fight the \nd Lord\nd*'s battles." For Saul said, "Let my hand not be on him, and let the hand of the Philistines be on him."
\v 18 And David said to Saul, "Who am I, and what is my father's family in Israel, that I should be the king's son-in-law?"
\v 19 And it happened when it was time to give Merob, Saul's daughter, to David, that she was afraid of David, and was given to Adriel the Meholathite for a wife.
\p
\v 20 And Michal, Saul's daughter, loved David, and they told Saul, and the thing was right in his eyes.
\v 21 And Saul said, "I will give her to him that she may be a snare to him, and that the hand of the Philistines may be on him." And Saul said to David a second time, "You will be my son-in-law today."
\v 22 And Saul commanded his servants, "Speak secretly to David, and say 'Behold, the king has delight in you, and all his servants love you; and now, be the king's son-in-law.'"
\p
\v 23 And Saul's servants spoke these words in David's ears, and David said, "Is it a light thing in your eyes to be the king's son-in-law? For I am a poor man, and lightly esteemed."
\v 24 And the servants of Saul told him, saying, "This is how David spoke."
\v 25 And Saul said, "Say thus to David: 'The king has no delight in a dowry except a hundred foreskins of the Philistines, to be avenged on the king's enemies.'" And Saul planned him to fall into the hand of the Philistines.
\v 26 And Saul's servants told David these words, and it was right in David's eyes to be the king's son-in-law. And the days had not been fulfilled,
\v 27 and David rose and went, he and his men, and struck a hundred Philistine men. And David brought their foreskins and gave them in full to the king, to be the king's son-in-law. And Saul gave him Michal his daughter for a wife.
\v 28 And Saul saw that the \nd Lord\nd* was with David, and Michal, his daughter, and all Israel loved him.
\v 29 And Saul was even more afraid before David, and Saul hated David continually.
\p
\v 30 And the captains of the Philistines went out, and it happened that whenever they went out, that David behaved himself more wisely that all the servants of Saul, and his name was greatly esteemed.
\c 19
\p
\v 1 And Saul spoke to Jonathan his son, and to all his servants, that they should kill David. And Jonathan, Saul's son, took much delight in David.
\v 2 And Jonathan told David, saying, "My father Saul is seeking to kill you, and please be watchful now in the morning, and hide yourself, and stay in a secret place,
\v 3 and I will go out and stand by my father in the field where you are, and I will speak to my father about you; and I will see what happens and I will tell you."
\v 4 And Jonathan spoke well of David to Saul his father, and said to him, "Let the king not sin against his servant, against David, for he hasn't sinned against you, and his works have been very good for you,
\v 5 for he put his soul in his hand and struck the Philistine, and the \nd Lord\nd* made a great salvation by his hand; and all Israel saw it and rejoiced; and why do you sin against innocent blood, to kill David for nothing?"
\v 6 And Saul paid attention to the voice of Jonathan, and Saul promised, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, he will not be killed."
\v 7 And Jonathan called to David and told him all these words. And Jonathan brought David to Saul, and he was before him as previously\f + \fr 19:7 \ft Hebrew, as yesterday and the third day.\f*.
\p
\v 8 And there was war again against the Philistines, and David went out and fought with the Philistines, and struck them with a very great slaughter; and they fled before him.
\p
\v 9 And an evil spirit from God was on Saul, as he sat in his house with his spear in his hand; and David was playing \add the harp\add* with his hand.
\v 10 And Saul sought to strike David with the spear; and he slipped away out of Saul's presence, and he struck the spear into the wall: and David fled, and escaped.
\v 11 And that night Saul sent messengers to David's house to watch him and to kill him in the morning: and Michal, David's wife, told him, saying, "If you don't save your soul tonight, you will be killed tomorrow."
\v 12 And Michal let David down through the window: and he went, and fled, and escaped.
\v 13 And Michal took the teraphim\f + \fr 19:13 \ft 'Teraphim' is some kind of household idol, although the exact nature is unknown. See Genesis 31:19, 30, 34.\f*, and laid it in the bed, and put a pillow of goats' \add hair\add* at its head, and covered it with the clothes.
\v 14 And Saul sent messengers to take David; and they said, "He is sick."
\v 15 And Saul sent the messengers to see David, saying, "Bring him up to me in the bed, that I may kill him."
\v 16 And when the messengers came in, behold, the teraphim was in the bed, with the pillow of goats' \add hair\add* at its head.
\v 17 And Saul said to Michal, "Why have you deceived me like this, and let my enemy go, and he has escaped?" And Michal answered Saul, "He said to me, 'Let me go; and if not, I will kill you.'"
\p
\v 18 And David fled, and escaped, and came to Samuel, to Ramah, and told him all that Saul had done to him. And he and Samuel went and stayed in Naioth.
\v 19 And it was told Saul, saying, "Behold, David is at Naioth in Ramah."
\v 20 And Saul sent messengers to take David: and they saw the company of the prophets prophesying, and Samuel standing as head over them, and the Spirit of God came upon the messengers of Saul, and they prophesied.
\v 21 And when it was told Saul, he sent other messengers, and they also prophesied. And Saul sent messengers again the third time, and they also prophesied. And Saul became angry.
\v 22 And he himself went to Ramah, and came as far as the well that is on the bare height. And he asked and said, "Where are Samuel and David?" And one said, "Behold, they are at Naioth in Ramah."
\v 23 And he went there to Naioth in Ramah: and the Spirit of God came upon him also, and he went on, and prophesied, until he came to Naioth in Ramah.
\v 24 And he stripped off his clothes, and he prophesied before them, and lay down naked all that day and all that night. Therefore they say, "Is Saul also among the prophets?"
\c 20
\p
\v 1 And David fled from Naioth in Ramah, and came before Jonathan and said, "What have I done? What is my iniquity and what is my sin before your father, that he seeks my soul?"
\v 2 And Jonathan said to him, "Far from it; you will not die: behold, my father does nothing either great or small that he doesn't uncover my ear; and why should my father hide this thing from me? It isn't so."
\v 3 And David answered Jonathan and said, "Your father knows well that I have found favour in your eyes, and he says, "Don't let Jonathan know this, lest he take counsel with David: and truly as the \nd Lord\nd* lives, and as your soul lives, he has promised \add an oath\add* between me and death.
\v 4 And Jonathan said to David, "Whatever your soul desires, I will also do it for you."
\v 5 And David said to Jonathan, "Behold, tomorrow is the new moon, and I should certainly sit with the king at meat: and let me go, that I may hide myself in the field until evening.
\v 6 If your father misses me at all, then say, 'David earnestly asked leave of me that he might run to Bethlehem his city; for it is the yearly sacrifice there for all the family.'
\v 7 If he says thus: 'It is well,' your servant will have peace: and if he answers you harshly, then you will know that evil is determined by him.
\v 8 And show lovingkindness to your servant; for you have brought your servant into a covenant of the \nd Lord\nd* with you: and if there is iniquity in me, kill me yourself; for why should you bring me to your father?"
\v 9 And Jonathan said, "Far be it from you; for if I should at all know that evil were determined by my father to come upon you, and if he came to your cities, I would tell you."
\v 10 And David said to Jonathan, "Who will tell me if your father answers you roughly?"
\v 11 And Jonathan said to David, "Come, and let us go out into the field." And they both went out into the field.
\v 12 And Jonathan said to David, "The \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, be witness: when I have sounded my father about this time tomorrow, \add or\add* the third day, behold, if there is good toward David, I will send to you in the field.
\v 13 God do so to Jonathan, and more also, if it pleases my father to do you evil, and I don't uncover your ear, and send you away, that you may go in peace: and the \nd Lord\nd* be with you, as he has been with my father.
\v 14 And if I am still alive, show me the lovingkindness of the \nd Lord\nd*; and if I die,
\v 15 don't cut off your lovingkindness from my house forever; and when the \nd Lord\nd* cuts off every one of the enemies of David from the face of the earth,
\v 16 if the name of Jonathan is cut of from the house of David, may the \nd Lord\nd* require it at the hand of David."
\v 17 And Jonathan promised to David again, for the love that he had to him; for he loved him as he loved his own soul.
\p
\v 18 And Jonathan said to him, "Tomorrow is the new moon: and you will be missed; because your seat will be missed.
\v 19 And since you will be missed on the third day, come to the place where you hid yourself when the work was in hand, and you will remain by the mound.
\v 20 And on the third day I will shoot an arrow on the side of it, as though I shot at a mark.
\v 21 And, behold, I will send the lad, \add saying\add*, 'Go, find the arrow.' If I say to the lad, 'Behold, the arrow is on this side of you;' take it, and come; for there is peace to you and there is no evil, as the \nd Lord\nd* lives.
\v 22 And if I say thus to the boy, 'Behold, the arrow is beyond you;' go your way; for the \nd Lord\nd* has sent you away.
\v 23 And as for the word which you and I have spoken, behold, the \nd Lord\nd* is a witness between you and me forever.
\p
\v 24 And David hid himself in the field, and when the new moon had come the king sat down to eat.
\v 25 And the king sat on his seat as at other times, on the seat by the wall; and Jonathan was in front, and Abiner sat by Saul's side: and David's place was missing.
\v 26 Nevertheless Saul didn't say anything that day for he thought, "Something has happened to him, he isn't clean; surely he isn't clean."
\v 27 And it happened on the next day after the new moon, the second \add day\add*, that David's place was missing. And Saul said to Jonathan his son, "Why doesn't the son of Jesse come to meat, neither yesterday nor today?"
\v 28 And Jonathan answered Saul, "David earnestly asked leave of me to go to Bethlehem his city,
\v 29 and he said, 'Let me go, I pray, for our family has a sacrifice in the city; and as for me, my brothers have commanded me \add to be there\add*: and now, if I have found favour in your eyes, please let me get away and see my brothers.' Therefore he hasn't come to the king's table."
\v 30 And Saul's anger was greatly kindled against Jonathan, and he said to him, "You son of a rebellious young woman, don't I know that you are in league with the son of Jesse to your own shame, and to the shame of your mother's nakedness?
\v 31 For all the days that the son of Jesse lives on the earth, you will not establish your kingdom. And now send and fetch him to me, for he is a son of death."
\v 32 And Jonathan answered Saul, "Why should he be put to death? what has he done?"
\v 33 And Saul raised his spear at him to strike him; and Jonathan knew that this evil was determined by his father to put David to death.
\v 34 And Jonathan sprang up from the table in fierce anger, and ate no food the second day of the month; because his father had shamed him.
\p
\v 35 And it happened in the morning that Jonathan went out into the field at the time appointed with David, and a little lad with him.
\v 36 And he said to his lad, "Run, find now the arrow which I shoot." And as the lad ran, he shot an arrow beyond him.
\v 37 And when the lad had come to the place of the arrow which Jonathan had shot, Jonathan called after the lad, and said, "Further; the arrow is beyond you."
\v 38 And Jonathan called after the lad, "Make speed, haste, don't stay." And Jonathan's lad gathered up the arrow, and came to his master.
\v 39 And the lad didn't know anything, only Jonathan and David knew the matter\f + \fr 20:39 \ft Hebrew, word.\f*.
\p
\v 40 And Jonathan gave his weapons to his lad, and said to him, "Go to the city."
\v 41 And as soon as the lad was gone, David rose out from the mound, and fell on his face to the ground, and bowed himself three times: and they kissed one another, and wept together greatly.
\v 42 And Jonathan said to David, "Go in peace, as we have both promised in the name of the \nd Lord\nd*, saying, 'The \nd Lord\nd* will be a witness between me and you, and between my seed and your seed, forever.'" And David rose and departed: and Jonathan went into the city.
\c 21
\p
\v 1 And David came to Nob, to Ahimelech the priest: and Ahimelech came to meet David trembling, and said to him, "Why are you alone, and no man with you?"
\v 2 And David said to Ahimelech the priest, "The king has commanded me a word today, and has said to me, 'Let no man know anything of the word on which I am sending you, and what I have commanded you; and I have appointed the young men to such and such a place.'
\v 3 And now, if there are five loaves of bread under your hand, give into my hand whatever can be found."
\v 4 And the priest answered David, and said, "There is no common bread under my hand, for there is holy bread; if the young men have kept themselves from women, then they may eat of it."
\v 5 And David answered the priest, and said to him, "Surely we have kept ourselves from women; in the past, when I set out on a journey, each of the young men was holy, even though it was a common journey; and how much more today, when they are sanctified together with the weapons?
\v 6 And Ahimelech the priest gave him the bread of the face; for there was no bread there except the bread of the face, that was taken from before the face of the \nd Lord\nd*, to put hot bread in the day when it was taken away.
\p
\v 7 And a certain man of the servants of Saul was there that day, detained before the \nd Lord\nd*; and his name was Doeg the Edomite, the keeper of Saul's mules.
\v 8 And David said to Ahimelech, "Is there here under your hand a spear or a sword? For I have brought neither my sword nor my weapons with me, because the king's word required haste."
\v 9 And the priest said, "The sword of Goliath the Philistine, who you killed in the valley of Elah, behold, it is here wrapped in a cloth behind the ephod. If you will take that, take it; for there is no other here except that." And David said, "There is none like that; give it to me."
\p
\v 10 And David rose, and fled that day for fear from Saul, and went to Achish the king of Gath.
\v 11 And the servants of Achish said to him, "Isn't this David, the king of the land? Didn't they sing one to another of him in dances, saying, 'Saul has killed his thousands, and David his ten thousands?'"
\v 12 And David laid up these words in his heart, and was very afraid of Achish the king of Gath.
\v 13 And he changed his face before him, and pretended to be mad in their hands, and spat on the doors of the gate, and let his spittle fall down upon his beard.
\v 14 And Achish said to his servants, "Behold, you see the man is mad; why have you brought him to me?
\v 15 Do I lack madmen, that you have brought this fellow to play the madman in my presence? Will this fellow come into my house?"
\c 22
\p
\v 1 And David went from there, and escaped, and came to the cave of Adullam. And when his brothers and all his father's house heard it, they went down to him there.
\v 2 And everyone who was in distress, and everyone who was in debt, and everyone who was bitter of soul, gathered themselves to him; and he became captain over them: and there were about four hundred men with him.
\p
\v 3 And David went from there to Mizpeh of Moab. And he said to the king of Moab, "Please let my father and my mother be with you till I know what God will do for me."
\v 4 And he brought them before the king of Moab, and they stayed with him all the days that David was in the stronghold.
\p
\v 5 And the prophet Gad said to David, "Don't stay in the stronghold; leave, and go into the land of Judah." And David left, and came and stayed in the city of Hereth.
\v 6 And Saul heard that David had been discovered. And Saul was sitting in Gibeah, under the tamarisk tree in Ramah, with his spear in his hand, and all his servants were standing around him.
\v 7 And Saul said to his servants who stood around him, "Hear now, you Benjamites! Will the son of Jesse give every one of you fields and vineyards, will he make you all captains of thousands and captains of hundreds,
\v 8 that all of you have conspired against me, and there is no one who uncovers my ear when my son makes \add a covenant\add* with the son of Jesse, and there is no one of you who has compassion for me, or uncovers my ear that my son has stirred up my servant against me, as an enemy, as at this day?"
\v 9 And Doeg the Edomite who stood by the donkeys of Saul, answered, and said, "I saw the son of Jesse coming to Nob, to Ahimelech the son of Ahitub the priest.
\v 10 And he inquired of the \nd Lord\nd* for him, and gave him victuals, and gave him the sword of Goliath the Philistine."
\p
\v 11 And the king sent to call Ahimelech the priest, the son of Ahitub, and all his father's house, the priests who were in Nob, and all of them came to the king.
\v 12 And Saul said, "Hear now, son of Ahitub." And he answered, "Here I am; speak, my lord."
\v 13 And Saul said to him, "Why have you conspired against me, you and the son of Jesse, in that you have given him bread, and a sword, and have inquired of God for him, that he should rise against me as an enemy, as at this day?"
\v 14 And Ahimelech answered the king, and said, "And who among all your servants is as faithful as David, who is the king's son-in-law, and is captain over your guard, and is honourable in your house?
\v 15 Have I today begun to inquire of God for him? Far be it from me: let the king not impute anything to his servant, nor to all the house of my father; for your servant knows nothing of all this, small or great."
\v 16 And the king said, "You will surely die, Ahimelech, you, and all your father's house."
\v 17 And the king said to the guard that stood about him, "Turn, and kill the priests of the \nd Lord\nd*; because their hand also is with David, and because they knew that he fled, and didn't uncover my ear. And the servants of the king would not put forth their hand to fall on the priests of the \nd Lord\nd*.
\v 18 And the king said to Doeg, "Turn and fall on the priests." And Doeg the Edomite turned, and he killed the priests of the \nd Lord\nd* on that day, eighty five persons who wore a linen ephod.
\v 19 And he struck Nob, the city of the priests, with the edge of the sword, from man even to woman, from child even to suckling, and ox and donkey and sheep, with the edge of the sword.
\v 20 And one of the sons of Ahimelech, the son of Ahitub, named Abiathar, escaped, and fled after David.
\v 21 And Abiathar told David that Saul had killed the \nd Lord\nd*'s priests.
\v 22 And David said to Abiathar, "I knew on that day, when Doeg the Edomite was there, that he would surely tell Saul. I am guilty of every soul of your father's house.
\v 23 Stay with me, don't fear; for he who seeks my soul seeks your soul: for with me you will be in \add safe\add* keeping."
\c 23
\p
\v 1 And they told David, saying, "Behold, the Philistines are fighting against Keilah, and are robbing the threshing-floors."
\v 2 And David inquired of the \nd Lord\nd*, saying, "Will I go and strike these Philistines?" And the \nd Lord\nd* said to David, "Go, and strike the Philistines, and save Keilah."
\v 3 And David's men said to him, "Behold, we are afraid here in Judah: and how much more if we go to Keilah into the remote parts of the Philistines?"
\v 4 And David inquired of the \nd Lord\nd* yet again. And the \nd Lord\nd* answered him, and said, "Arise, go down to Keilah; for I will deliver the Philistines into your hand."
\v 5 And David and his men went to Keilah, and fought with the Philistines, and they fled before him, and they brought away their cattle, and killed them with a great slaughter. And David saved the inhabitants of Keilah.
\p
\v 6 And it happened, when Abiathar the son of Ahimelech fled to David at Keilah, that he came down with an ephod in his hand.
\v 7 And it was told to Saul that David had come to Keilah. And Saul said, "God has sold him into my hand; for he is shut in, by entering into a town that has gates and bars."
\v 8 And Saul summoned all the people to war, to go down to Keilah, to besiege David and his men.
\v 9 And David knew that Saul was devising mischief against him; and he said to Abiathar the priest, "Bring the ephod of the \nd Lord\nd* here."
\v 10 And David said, "O \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, your servant has surely heard that Saul seeks to come to Keilah, to destroy the city for my sake.
\v 11 And now, will Saul come down, as your servant has heard? O \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, please tell your servant." And the \nd Lord\nd* said, "He will come down."
\v 12 And David said, "Will the masters of Keilah deliver me and my men up into the hand of Saul?" And the \nd Lord\nd* said, "They will deliver you up."
\v 13 And David and his men, about six hundred men, rose and departed out of Keilah, and went wherever they could go. And it was told to Saul that David had escaped from Keilah; and he refrained from going forth.
\p
\v 14 And David stayed in the wilderness in the strongholds, and stayed in the hill-country in the wilderness of Ziph. And Saul sought him every day, and the \nd Lord\nd* didn't deliver him into his hand.
\v 15 And David was afraid, for Saul had come out to seek his soul, and David was in the wilderness of Ziph in the wood.
\v 16 And Jonathan, Saul's son, rose, and went to David, into the wood, and strengthened his hand in God.
\v 17 And he said to him, "Don't fear; for the hand of Saul my father will not find you; and you will be king over Israel, and I will be next to you; and my father Saul knows this also."
\v 18 And the two of them made a covenant before the \nd Lord\nd*. And David stayed in the wood, and Jonathan went to his house.
\v 19 And the Ziphites came up to Saul, to Gibeah, saying, "Behold, David is hiding himself with us in the strongholds in the wood, in the hill of Hachilah, which is on the south of the desert.
\v 20 And now come down, according to all the desire of the king to come down, let him come down; and our part will be to deliver him up into the king's hand."
\v 21 And Saul said, "You are blessed of the \nd Lord\nd*; for you have had compassion on me.
\v 22 Please go and make even more sure, and know, and see his place where his foot hastens;" for he said, "Perhaps he is very cunning.
\v 23 And see, and find out all the lurking-places where he hides himself, and be sure to come again to me, and I will go with you: and it will happen that if he is in the land I will search him out among all the thousands of Judah."
\v 24 And they rose, and went to Ziph before Saul: and David and his men were in the wilderness of Simeon, in the plain on the south of the desert.
\v 25 And Saul and his men went to search for him. And they told David, and he came down to the rock which is in the wilderness of Simeon. And when Saul heard, he pursued David in the wilderness of Simeon.
\v 26 And Saul went on this side of the mountain, and David and his men on the other side of the mountain: and David hurried to get away for fear of Saul and his men; for Saul and his men were crossing over against David and his men round about, to take them.
\v 27 And a messenger came to Saul, saying, "Hurry, and come; for the Philistines have made a raid on the land."
\v 28 And Saul returned from pursuing David, and went against the Philistines: therefore they called that place The Rock of Divisions\f + \fr 23:28 \ft The word here for divisions is as in the Word on the Generations and the Kings (so-called 1 Chr chapter 27).\f*.
\v 29 \f + \fr 23:29 \ft Some editions count chapter 24 from this verse.\f*And David went up from there, and dwelt in the strongholds of En-gedi.
\c 24
\p
\v 1 And it happened that when Saul had returned from following the Philistines it was told him, saying, "Behold, David is in the wilderness of En-gedi."
\v 2 And Saul took three thousand chosen men out of all Israel, and went to seek David and his men upon the rocks of the wild goats.
\v 3 And he came to the sheep enclosures by the way, where there was a cave; and Saul went in to cover his feet. And David and his men were staying in the innermost parts of the cave.
\v 4 And the men of David said to him, "Behold, the day of which the \nd Lord\nd* said to you, 'Behold, I will give your enemy into your hand, and you will do to him as it will be good in your eyes.'" And David rose, and cut off the skirt of Saul's robe secretly.
\v 5 And it happened afterward, that David's heart struck him, because he had cut off the edge of Saul's robe.
\v 6 And he said to his men, "Far be it from me before the \nd Lord\nd* that I should do this thing to the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed, to put forth my hand against him, seeing he is the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed."
\v 7 And David persuaded his men with these words, and didn't let them rise and kill Saul. And Saul rose up out of the cave, and went on his way.
\p
\v 8 And David rose afterward, and went out of the cave, and cried after Saul, saying, "My lord the king." And when Saul looked behind him, David bowed with his face to the earth, and prostrated himself.
\v 9 And David said to Saul, "Why do you listen to men's words, saying, 'Behold, David seeks your soul?'
\v 10 Behold, this day your eyes have seen how that the \nd Lord\nd* had given you today into my hand in the cave: and I refused to kill you, and spared you; and I said, 'I will not put forth my hand against my lord; for he is the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed.'
\v 11 And see the skirt of your robe in my hand; for in that I cut off the skirt of your robe, and didn't kill you, know and see that there is neither evil nor transgression in my hand, and I haven't sinned against you, though you hunt my soul to take it.
\v 12 The \nd Lord\nd* judge between me and you, and the \nd Lord\nd* avenge me of you; and my hand will not be upon you.
\v 13 As the proverb of the ancients says, 'Out of the wicked comes forth wickedness;' and my hand will not be upon you.
\v 14 And now, who have you come out after, O the king of Israel? Who do you pursue? After a dead dog, after a flea?
\v 15 And the \nd Lord\nd* be judge, and give justice between me and you, and see, and plead my cause, and give me justice out of your hand."
\p
\v 16 And it happened, when David had finished speaking these words to Saul, that Saul said, "Is this your voice, my son David?" And Saul lifted up his voice, and wept.
\v 17 And he said to David, "You are more righteous than I; for you have rendered good to me, and I have rendered evil to you.
\v 18 And you have declared to me this day how that you have dealt well with me, in that when the \nd Lord\nd* had delivered me up into your hand, you didn't kill me.
\v 19 For if a man finds his enemy, will he let him go on a good way? And the \nd Lord\nd* will reward you with good for that which you have done to me this day.
\v 20 And now, behold, I know that you will surely be king, and that the kingdom of Israel will be established in your hand.
\v 21 And now promise to me by the \nd Lord\nd*, that you will not cut off my seed after me, and that you will not destroy my name out of my father's house.
\v 22 And David promised to Saul. And Saul went home; and David and his men went up to the stronghold.
\c 25
\p
\v 1 And Samuel died; and all Israel gathered themselves together, and lamented him, and buried him in his house at Ramah. And David rose, and went down to the wilderness of Simeon.
\p
\v 2 And there was a man in the wilderness, whose possessions were in Carmel; and the man was very great, and he had three thousand sheep, and a thousand goats: and he was shearing his sheep in Carmel.
\v 3 And the man's name was Nabal\f + \fr 25:3 \ft Nabal (\tl נבל\tl*) means Fool.\f*; and the name of his wife was Abigail; and the woman was of good understanding, and of a beautiful countenance: and the man was churlish and evil in his doings; and he was a Calebite.
\v 4 And David heard in the wilderness that Nabal was shearing his sheep.
\v 5 And David sent ten young men, and David said to the young men, "Go up to Carmel, and go to Nabal, and ask him as to his peace in my name:
\v 6 and thus you will say to my brother, 'Peace to you, and peace to your house, and peace to all that you have.
\v 7 And now I have heard that you have shearers: your shepherds have been with us in the wilderness, and we did them no harm, neither was there anything missing to them, all the while they were in Carmel.
\v 8 Ask your young men, and they will tell you: and let the young men find favour in your eyes; for we come in a good day: please give whatever comes to your hand to your servants and to your son David.'"
\p
\v 9 And when David's young men came, they spoke to Nabal according to all those words in the name of David, and he sprang up.
\v 10 And Nabal answered David's servants, and said, "Who is David and who is the son of Jesse? There are many servants today who break away every man from his master.
\v 11 And will I take my bread, and my wine, and my flesh that I have killed for my shearers, and give it to men not knowing where they are from?"
\v 12 And David's young men turned on their way, and went back, and came and told him according to all these words.
\v 13 And David said to his men, "Every man gird on his sword." And every man girded on his sword; and David also girded on his sword: and there went up after David about four hundred men; and two hundred stayed by the baggage.
\p
\v 14 And one of the young men told Abigail, Nabal's wife, saying, "Behold, David sent messengers out of the wilderness to bless our master; and he railed at them.
\v 15 And the men were very good to us, and we weren't hurt, neither did we miss anything, as long as we went with them, when we were in the fields:
\v 16 they were a wall to us both by night and by day, all the days we were with them keeping the sheep.
\v 17 And now know and see what you will do; for evil is determined against our master, and against all his house: for he is such a son of belial\f + \fr 25:17 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f* that one cannot speak to him."
\v 18 And Abigail made haste, and took two hundred loaves, and two bottles of wine, and five sheep made ready, and five seahs of parched grain, and one omer of raisins, and two hundred cakes of figs, and laid them on donkeys.
\v 19 And she said to her young men, "Go on before me; behold, I come after you." And she didn't tell her husband Nabal.
\v 20 And it happened, as she rode on her donkey, and came up by the covert of the mountain, that behold, David and his men came down toward her; and she met them.
\v 21 And David had said, "Surely in vain have I kept all that this fellow has in the wilderness, and nothing was missed of all that was his: and he has returned me evil for good.
\v 22 God do so to David, and more also, if I leave of all that are his by the morning light one that passes urine against the wall."
\p
\v 23 And when Abigail saw David, she hurried, and dismounted from her donkey, and fell before David on her face, and bowed herself to the ground
\v 24 at his feet, and said, "Upon me, my lord, be the iniquity; and please let your handmaid speak in your ears, and hear the words of your handmaid.
\v 25 Please let my lord not regard this man of belial\f + \fr 25:25 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f*, Nabal; for as his name is, so is he; Nabal is his name, and folly is with him: and I, your handmaid, didn't see the young men of my lord, who you sent.
\v 26 And now, my lord, as the \nd Lord\nd* lives, and as your soul lives, seeing the \nd Lord\nd* has withheld you from coming in with innocent blood, and from saving yourself with your own hand, and now let your enemies, and them that seek evil to my lord, be as Nabal.
\v 27 And now take this blessing which your servant has brought to my lord, and let it be given to the young men who follow my lord.
\v 28 Please forgive the trespass of your handmaid: for the \nd Lord\nd* will certainly make my lord a faithful house, because my lord fights the battles of the \nd Lord\nd*; and evil will not be found in you all your days.
\v 29 And though men rise up to pursue you, and to seek your soul, yet the soul of my lord will be bound in the bundle of life with the \nd Lord\nd* your God; and he will sling out the souls of your enemies, in the hollow of a sling.
\v 30 And it will happen, when the \nd Lord\nd* will have done to my lord according to all the good that he has spoken concerning you, and will have appointed you prince over Israel,
\v 31 that this will be no grief to you, nor offence of heart to my lord, neither that you have shed innocent blood without cause, nor that my lord has saved himself. And when the \nd Lord\nd* will have dealt well with my lord, then remember your handmaid."
\p
\v 32 And David said to Abigail, "Blessed be the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, who sent you this day to meet me:
\v 33 and blessed be your discretion, and blessed be you, who have kept me this day from coming in with blood, and from saving myself with my own hand.
\v 34 For in very deed, as the \nd Lord\nd*, the God of Israel, lives, who has withheld me from doing evil to you, unless you had hurried and come to meet me, surely there would not have been left to Nabal by the morning light one that passes urine against the wall.
\v 35 And David received from her hand that which she had brought him: and he said to her, "Go up in peace to your house; see, I have listened to your voice, and have lifted up your face."
\p
\v 36 And Abigail came to Nabal; and, behold, he held a feast in his house, like the feast of a king; and Nabal's heart was merry within him, for he was very drunk: and she didn't tell him a word, less or more, until the morning light.
\v 37 And it happened in the morning, when the wine had gone out of Nabal, that his wife told him these things, and his heart died within him, and he became as a stone.
\v 38 And it happened about ten days after, that the \nd Lord\nd* struck Nabal, and he died.
\v 39 And when David heard that Nabal was dead, he said, "Blessed be the \nd Lord\nd*, who has pleaded the cause of my reproach from the hand of Nabal, and has kept back his servant from the hand of evil-doers: and the \nd Lord\nd* has returned the evil-doing of Nabal upon his own head."
\p
And David sent and spoke concerning Abigail, to take her to him as a wife.
\v 40 And when the servants of David had come to Abigail to Carmel, they spoke to her, saying, "David has sent us to you, to take you to him as a wife."
\v 41 And she rose, and bowed herself with her face to the earth, and said, "Behold, your handmaid is a servant to wash the feet of the servants of my lord."
\v 42 And Abigail hurried, and rose, and rode upon a donkey, with five maids of hers that followed her; and she went after the messengers of David, and became his wife.
\v 43 David also took Ahinoam of Jezreel; and they both became his wives.
\v 44 And Saul had given Michal his daughter, David's wife, to Palti the son of Laish, who was of Gallim.
\c 26
\p
\v 1 And the Ziphites came to Saul at Gibeah, saying, "Behold, David is hiding himself with us in the hill of Hachilah, which is before the desert."
\v 2 And Saul rose, and went down to the wilderness of Ziph with three thousand chosen men of Israel to seek David in the wilderness of Ziph.
\v 3 And Saul camped in the hill of Hachilah, which is before the desert, by the way. And David stayed in the wilderness, and he saw that Saul came after him into the wilderness.
\v 4 And David sent out spies, and understood that Saul was coming to Hachilah.
\v 5 And David rose in secret, and came to the place where Saul had camped; and David saw the place where Saul lay; and there was Abiner the son of Ner, the captain of his host. And Saul lay within the track, and the people were camped round about him.
\p
\v 6 And David answered and said to Ahimelech the Hittite, and to Abishai the son of Zeruiah, brother to Joab, saying, "Who will go down with me to Saul, to the camp?" And Abishai said, "I will go down with you."
\v 7 And David and Abishai came to the people by night: and behold, Saul lay sleeping within the track with his spear stuck in the ground at his head; and Abiner and the people lay round about him.
\v 8 And Abishai said to David, "The \nd Lord\nd* has delivered up your enemy into your hand this day: and now please let me strike him with the spear to the earth at one stroke, and I will not repeat it to him."
\v 9 And David said to Abishai, "Don't destroy him, for who puts forth his hand against the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed and is guiltless?"
\v 10 And David said, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, the \nd Lord\nd* will strike him, or his day will come to die, or he will go down into battle and perish.
\v 11 Far be it from be before the \nd Lord\nd* that I should put forth my hand against the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed: and now please take the spear that is at his head, and the jar of water, and let us go."
\v 12 And David took the spear and the jar of water from Saul's head; and they went away: and no man saw it, nor knew it, neither did any awake; for they were all asleep, because a deep sleep from the \nd Lord\nd* had fallen on them.
\p
\v 13 And David went over to the other side, and stood on the top of the mountain a long way off, with a great space between them;
\v 14 and David called to the people, and to Abiner the son of Ner, saying, "Don't you answer, Abiner?" And Abiner answered and said, "Who is it who calls to me?"
\v 15 And David said to Abiner, "Aren't you a man, and who is like you in Israel? And why haven't you kept watch over your lord the king? For one of the people came in to destroy the king your lord.
\v 16 This thing\f + \fr 26:16 \ft Hebrew, word.\f* that you have done isn't good. As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, you are sons of death, because you haven't kept watch over your lord, the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed. And now see where the king's spear is, and the jar of water that was at his head.
\p
\v 17 And Saul knew David's voice, and said, "Is this your voice, my son David?" And David said, "It is your servant, my lord, O king."
\v 18 And David said, "Why does my lord the king pursue his servant? For how have I sinned, and what evil is found in me?
\v 19 And now please let my lord the king hear the words of his servant. If it be God who has stirred you up against me, let him smell an offering: and if it be the children of men, let them be cursed before the \nd Lord\nd*: for they have driven me out this day that I should not hold fast to the inheritance of the \nd Lord\nd*, saying, "Go, serve other gods."
\v 20 And now, don't let my blood fall to the earth away from the face of the \nd Lord\nd*: for the king of Israel has come out to seek my soul, as one hunts a partridge in the mountains.
\p
\v 21 And Saul said, "I have sinned: return, my son David; for I will not do evil to you any more, because my soul was precious in your eyes this day: behold, I have played the fool, and have erred exceedingly."
\v 22 And David answered and said, "Behold the king's spear! And let one of the young men come over and fetch it.
\v 23 And the \nd Lord\nd* will render to every man his righteousness and his faithfulness; for the \nd Lord\nd* gave you into my hand today, and I would not put forth my hand against the \nd Lord\nd*'s anointed.
\v 24 And behold, as your soul was highly regarded in my eyes this day, so let my soul be highly regarded in the eyes of the \nd Lord\nd*, and let him deliver me out of all distress."
\v 25 And Saul said to David, "May you be blessed, my son David: you will both do mightily, and will surely prevail." And David went his way, and Saul returned to his place.
\c 27
\p
\v 1 And David said in his heart, "I will now perish one day by the hand of Saul: there is nothing better for me except that I escape into the land of the Philistines; and Saul will despair of me, to seek me any more in all the borders of Israel: and I will escape out of his hand."
\v 2 And David rose, and passed over, he and the six hundred men who were with him, to Achish the son of Maoch, king of Gath.
\v 3 And David stayed with Achish at Gath, he and his men, every man with his household, even David with his two wives, Ahinoam the Jezreelitess, and Abigail the Carmelite, Nabal's wife.
\v 4 And it was told Saul that David had fled to Gath: and he didn't look for him any more.
\v 5 And David said to Achish, "If now your servant has found favour in your eyes, let them give me a place in one of the cities in the country, that I may stay there: for why should your servant stay in the royal city with you?"
\v 6 And Achish gave him Ziklag that day: therefore Ziklag belongs to the kings of Judah to this day.
\v 7 And the number of the days that David stayed in the country of the Philistines was four months.
\p
\v 8 And David and his men went up, and made a raid upon the Geshurites, and the Girzites, and the Amalekites; for the land was inhabited from of old, as you go to Shur, and to Egypt.
\v 9 And David struck the land, and saved neither man nor woman alive, and took away the sheep, and the oxen, and the donkeys, and the camels, and the apparel; and he returned, and came to Achish.
\v 10 And Achish said, "Who have you made a raid against today?" And David said, "Against the South of Judah, and against the South of the Jerahmeelites, and against the South of the Kenizzites."
\v 11 And David saved neither man nor woman alive, to bring them to Gath, saying, "Lest they should tell Gath of us, saying, 'So did David, and so has been his justice all the days he has stayed in the country of the Philistines.'"
\v 12 And Achish believed David, saying, "He has made his people Israel utterly to abhor him; and he will be my servant for ever."
\c 28
\p
\v 1 And it happened in those days, that the Philistines gathered their hosts together for warfare, to fight with Israel. And Achish said to David, "Know that you will surely go out with me to battle, you and your men."
\v 2 And David said to Achish, "Therefore you will know what your servant will do." And Achish said to David, "Therefore I will make you keeper of my head for ever."
\p
\v 3 And Samuel was dead, and all Israel had lamented him, and buried him in Ramah his own city. And Saul had put away the necromancers, and the wizards, out of the land.
\v 4 And the Philistines gathered themselves together, and came and camped in Shunem: and Saul gathered all Israel together, and they camped in Gilboa.
\p
\v 5 And when Saul saw the host of the Philistines, he was afraid, and his heart trembled greatly.
\v 6 And when Saul inquired of the \nd Lord\nd*, the \nd Lord\nd* didn't answer him, neither by dreams, nor by Urim, nor by prophets.
\v 7 And Saul said to his servants, "Find me a woman who is a mistress of necromancy, that I may go to her, and inquire of her." And his servants said to him, "Behold, there is a woman who is a mistress of necromancy at En-dor."
\v 8 And Saul disguised himself, and put on other clothes, and went, he and two men with him, and they came to the woman by night: and he said, "Please divine to me by necromancy, and bring me up whoever I will say to you."
\v 9 And the woman said to him, "Behold, you know what Saul has done, how he has cut off the necromancers, and the wizards, out of the land: and why do you lay a snare for my soul, to cause me to die?"
\v 10 And Saul promised to her by the \nd Lord\nd*, saying, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, no punishment will happen to you for this thing\f + \fr 28:10 \ft Hebrew, word.\f*."
\p
\v 11 And the woman said, "Who will I bring up to you?" And he said, "Bring me up Samuel."
\v 12 And when the woman saw Samuel, she cried with a loud voice; and the woman spoke to Saul, saying, "Why have you deceived me? for you are Saul."
\v 13 And the king said to her, "Don't be afraid: for what do you see? Speak." And the woman said to Saul, "I see a god coming up out of the earth."
\v 14 And he said to her, "What form does he have?" And she said, "An upright man is coming up; and he is covered with a robe." And Saul perceived that it was Samuel, and he bowed with his face to the ground, and bowed down to him.
\v 15 And Samuel said to Saul, "Why have you disquieted me, to bring me up?" And Saul answered, "I am severely distressed; for the Philistines make war against me, and God has departed from me, and answers me no more, neither by prophets, nor by dreams: and I have called you, that you may make known to me what I will do."
\v 16 And Samuel said, "And why do you ask of me, seeing the \nd Lord\nd* has departed from you to be with your neighbour?
\v 17 And the \nd Lord\nd* has done to you as he spoke by me: and the \nd Lord\nd* has torn the kingdom out of your hand, and given it to your neighbour, to David.
\v 18 Because you didn't listen to the voice of the \nd Lord\nd*, and didn't execute his fierce wrath upon Amalek, therefore the \nd Lord\nd* has done this word to you this day.
\v 19 And the \nd Lord\nd* will deliver Israel also with you into the hand of the Philistines; and tomorrow you and your sons will fall; and the \nd Lord\nd* will also give the host of Israel into the hand of the Philistines."
\p
\v 20 And Saul fell straight away his full length upon the earth, and was very afraid, because of the words of Samuel: and there was no strength in him; for he had eaten no bread all the day, nor all the night.
\v 21 And the woman came to Saul, and saw that he was very troubled, and said to him, "Behold, your handmaid has listened to your voice, and I have put my soul in my hand, and have listened to your words which you spoke to me.
\v 22 And now please you also listen to the voice of your handmaid, and let me set a morsel of bread before you; and eat, that you may have strength, when you go on your way."
\v 23 And he refused, and would not eat. And his servants, together with the woman, urged him; and he listened to their voice. And he rose from the earth, and sat on the bed.
\v 24 And the woman had a fatted calf in the house; and she hurried, and killed it; and she took flour, and kneaded it, and baked unleavened bread from it:
\v 25 and she brought it before Saul, and before his servants; and they ate. And they rose up, and went away that night.
\c 29
\p
\v 1 And the Philistines gathered together all their hosts to Aphek: and the Israelites camped by the fountain which is in Jezreel.
\v 2 And the lords of the Philistines passed on by hundreds, and by thousands; and David and his men passed on in the rear with Achish.
\v 3 And the princes of the Philistines said, "What are these Hebrews?" And Achish said to the princes of the Philistines, "Isn't this David, the servant of Saul the king of Israel, who has been with me these days this year, and I have found no fault in him from the time he fell to me to this day?"
\v 4 And the princes of the Philistines were angry with him; and they said to him, "Make the man return, that he may go back to his place where you have appointed him, and let him not go down with us to battle, and be an adversary in the camp: for how should this fellow reconcile himself with his lord if not with the heads of these men?
\v 5 Isn't this David, who they answered one another about in dances, saying, 'Saul has slain his thousands, and David his ten thousands?'"
\p
\v 6 And Achish called David, and said to him, "As the \nd Lord\nd* lives, you have been upright, and your going out and your coming in with me in the host is good in my eyes; for I haven't found evil in you since the day of your coming to me to this day: nevertheless you are not good in the eyes of the lords.
\v 7 And now return, and go in peace, and you will not do evil in the eyes of the lords of the Philistines."
\v 8 And David said to Achish, "For what have I done, and what have you found in your servant so long as I have been before you to this day, that I may not go and fight against the enemies of my lord the king?"
\v 9 And Achish answered and said to David, "I know that you are good in my eyes, as an angel of God: however the princes of the Philistines have said, "He will not go up with us to the battle."
\v 10 And now arise early in the morning, you and the servants of your lord who have come with you, and go to the place which I appointed for you. And as for evil words, take none to heart, for you have been good in my eyes. And arise early for the road, and when you have light, depart."
\v 11 And David rose up early, he and his men, to depart in the morning, to return into the land of the Philistines. And the Philistines went up to Jezreel.
\c 30
\p
\v 1 And it happened when David and his men had come to Ziklag on the third day, that the Amalekites had made a raid upon the South, and upon Ziklag, and had struck Ziklag, and burned it with fire,
\v 2 and of the women, and of all who were in it, both small and great, they didn't kill anyone; and they carried them off captive, and went their way.
\v 3 And when David and his men came to the city, behold, it was burned with fire; and their wives, and their sons, and their daughters, were taken captive.
\v 4 And David and the people who were with him lifted up their voice and wept, until they had no more power to weep.
\v 5 And David's two wives were taken captive, Ahinoam the Jezreelitess, and Abigail the wife of Nabal the Carmelite.
\v 6 And David was greatly distressed; for the people spoke of stoning him, because the soul of all the people was grieved, every man for his sons and for his daughters: and David strengthened himself in the \nd Lord\nd* his God.
\p
\v 7 And David said to Abiathar the priest, the son of Ahimelech, "Please bring the ephod here to me." And Abiathar brought the ephod to David.
\v 8 And David asked the \nd Lord\nd*, saying, "Will I pursue this troop? Will I overtake them?" And he answered him, "Pursue; for you will surely overtake, and will surely deliver \add them\add*."
\v 9 And David went, he and the six hundred men who were with him, and came to the brook Besor, and those who were left behind stayed.
\v 10 And David pursued, he and four hundred men; for two hundred stayed behind, who were so faint that they couldn't go over the brook Besor.
\p
\v 11 And they found an Egyptian in the field, and brought him to David, and gave him bread, and he ate; and they gave him water to drink.
\v 12 And they gave him a piece of a cake of figs, and two clusters of raisins: and when he had eaten, his spirit came to him again; for he had eaten no bread, nor drunk any water, three days and three nights.
\v 13 And David said to him, "Who do you belong to and where are you from?" And he said, "I am a young man of Egypt, servant to an Amalekite; and my master left me, because three days ago I fell sick.
\v 14 We made a raid upon the South of the Cherethites, and upon that which belongs to Judah, and upon the South of Caleb; and we burned Ziklag with fire."
\v 15 And David said to him, "Will you bring me down to this troop?" And he said, "Promise to me by God, that you will neither kill me, nor deliver me up into the hands of my master, and I will bring you down to this troop." And he promised to him.
\p
\v 16 And when he had brought him down, behold, they were spread abroad over all the ground, eating and drinking, and dancing, because of all the great spoil that they had taken out of the land of the Philistines, and out of the land of Judah.
\v 17 And David went against them and struck them from the twilight even to the evening of the next day, and he put them to death; and not a man of them escaped, except four hundred young men, who rode upon camels and fled.
\v 18 And David delivered all that the Amalekites had taken; and David delivered his two wives.
\v 19 And nothing that belonged to them was missing, neither small nor great, neither sons nor daughters, neither spoil, nor anything that they had taken to them: David brought back all.
\v 20 And David took all the flocks and the herds, and he drove them ahead of the spoil; and they said, "This is David's spoil."
\p
\v 21 And David came to the two hundred men, who were so faint that they couldn't follow David, those they had made to stay at the brook Besor; and they went out to meet David, and to meet the people who were with him: and when David came near to the people, he asked them as to \add their\add* peace.
\v 22 And all the evil men and ones of belial\f + \fr 30:22 \ft "son of belial" or "daughter of belial" is a Hebrew idiom meaning 'worthless' or 'wicked'.\f*, of those who went with David, answered and said, "Because they didn't pursue with us, we will not give them any of the spoil that we have delivered, except to every man his wife and his children, that they may lead them away, and depart."
\v 23 And David said, "You will not do so, my brothers, after the \nd Lord\nd* has given us the adversaries, and he has preserved us, and delivered the troop that came against us into our hand.
\v 24 And who will listen to you in this word? For they are not less than you; for the share of him who waits by the baggage will be as the share of him who goes down to the battle: they will share alike."
\v 25 And it was so from that day forward, that it became a statute and an ordinance for Israel to this day.
\p
\v 26 And when David came to Ziklag, he sent of the spoil to the elders of Judah, and to his friends, saying, "Behold, a blessing for you of the spoil of the enemies of the \nd Lord\nd*,"
\v 27 to those who were in Beth-zur, and to those who were in Ramoth of the South, and to those who were in Jattir,
\v 28 and to those who were in Aroer, and to those who were in Siphmoth, and to those who were in Eshtemoa,
\v 29 and to those who were in Carmel, and to those who were in the cities of the Jerahmeelites, and to those who were in the cities of the Kenizzites,
\v 30 and to those who were in Hormah, and to those who were in Beer-sheba, and to those who were in Athach,
\v 31 and to those who were in Hebron, and to all the places where David himself and his men had gone up and down.
\c 31
\p
\v 1 And the Philistines fought against Israel: and the men of Israel fled from before the Philistines, and fell down killed in mount Gilboa.
\v 2 And the Philistines followed hard on Saul and his sons; and the Philistines killed Jonathan, and Abinadab, and Malchi-shua, the sons of Saul.
\v 3 And the battle went very badly against Saul, and the archers found him; and he was greatly wounded in the belly.
\v 4 And Saul said to his armour bearer, "Draw your sword, and thrust me through with it, lest these uncircumcised come and thrust me through, and abuse me." And his armour bearer would not; for he was very afraid. And Saul took his sword, and fell upon it.
\v 5 And when his armour bearer saw that Saul was dead, he likewise fell upon his sword, and died with him.
\v 6 And Saul died, and his three sons, and his armour bearer, and all his men, that same day together.
\p
\v 7 And when the men of Israel who were on the other side of the valley, and those who were beyond the Jordan, saw that the men of Israel fled, and that Saul and his sons were dead, they abandoned the cities, and fled; and the Philistines came and stayed in them.
\v 8 And it happened on the next day, when the Philistines came to strip the slain, that they found Saul and his three sons fallen on Mount Gilboa.
\v 9 And they cut off his head, and stripped off his armour, and sent into the land of the Philistines round about, to carry the tidings to their idols, and to the people.
\v 10 And they put his armour in the house of the Ashtaroth\f + \fr 31:10 \ft Ashtaroth is plural of Ashtoreth, the name of a Canaanite goddess supposedly associated with the moon and fertility.\f*; and they fastened his body to the wall of Beth-shan.
\v 11 And when the inhabitants of Jabesh-gilead heard concerning him that which the Philistines had done to Saul,
\v 12 all the valiant men arose, and went all night, and took the body of Saul and the bodies of his sons from the wall of Beth-shan; and they came to Jabesh, and burnt them there.
\v 13 And they took their bones, and buried them under the tamarisk-tree in Jabesh, and fasted seven days.
